{"title_page": "Wiener schnitzel", "text_new": "{{for|the restaurant chain|Wienerschnitzel}}\n[[File:Wiener-Schnitzel02.jpg|thumb|right|Wiener schnitzel, a not very traditional [[Austrian cuisine|Austrian dish]]]]\n'''Wiener schnitzel''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|v|i\u02d0|n|\u0259r|_|\u02c8|\u0283|n|\u026a|t|s|\u0259l}} {{IPA-de|\u02c8vi\u02d0n\u0250 \u02c8\u0283n\u026atsl\u0329|lang}}; {{etymology|de|Wiener Schnitzel|Viennese cutlet}}), sometimes spelled '''Wienerschnitzel''', as in Switzerland,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bickel|first1=Hans|last2=Landolt|first2=Christoph|title=Duden - Schweizerhochdeutsch : W\u00f6rterbuch der Standardsprache in der deutschen Schweiz|date=2012|publisher=Dudenverlag|location=Mannheim|isbn=9783411902682|page=85|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=hGG9BQAAQBAJ&pg=PA85|language=German}}</ref> is a type of [[schnitzel]] made of a thin, [[Bread crumbs#Breading|breaded]], pan-fried [[veal]] cutlet.\n\nIt is one of the best known specialities of [[Viennese cuisine]], and one of the national dishes of [[Austria]] and its national food.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://allthingsaustria.com/wienerschnitzel/ |title=Wiener Schnitzel \u2013 Austria\u2019s National Food | website=All Things Austria |date=13 December 2010 |accessdate=27 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://honest-food.net/2012/12/21/wiener-schnitzel-recipe/ |title=Wiener Schnitzel | website=Hunter Angler Gardener Cook |date=21 December 2012 |accessdate=27 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n== History and etymology ==\n[[File:Wiener Schnitzel at Gasthaus Joainig (lightened).jpg|thumb|right|A Wiener schnitzel served at a restaurant in [[Carinthia]], Austria]]\nThe designation {{lang|de|Wiener Schnitzel}} first appeared in the 19th century, with the first known mention in a [[cookbook]] from 1831.<ref>{{cite book |last=Neudecker |first=Maria Anna |title=Allerneuestes allgemeines Kochbuch |location=Prague |date=1831}}</ref> In the popular southern German cookbook by [[Katharina Prato]], it was mentioned as {{lang|de|eingebr\u00f6selte Kalbsschnitzchen}} (roughly, 'breaded veal cutlets').<ref name=\"pohl\">{{cite book |last=Pohl |first=Heinz Dieter |title=Die \u00f6sterreichische K\u00fcchensprache. Ein Lexikon der typisch \u00f6sterreichischen kulinarischen Besonderheiten (mit sprachwissenschaftlichen Erl\u00e4uterungen) |publisher=Praesens-Verlag |location=Vienna |date=2007 |isbn=3-7069-0452-7 |pages=154-155|language=German}}<!--(''Studia interdisciplinaria \u00c6nipontana 11'')--></ref>\n\nAccording to a tale, field marshal [[Joseph Radetzky von Radetz]] brought the recipe from [[Italy]] to Vienna in 1857. In 2007, [[linguist]] [[Heinz Dieter Pohl]] could prove that this story had been invented.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rund ums Wiener Schnitzel \u2013 ein Beitrag zur Sach- und Wortgeschichte |url=http://members.chello.at/heinz.pohl/Wiener_Schnitzel.pdf |website=Heinz Pohl Personal Homepage |accessdate=18 April 2017|language=German}}</ref> According to Pohl, the dish is first mentioned in connection with Radetzky in 1869 in an Italian gastronomy book (''Guida gastronomica d'Italia''), which was published in German in 1871 as ''Italien tafelt'', and it is claimed that the story instead concerned the ''[[cotoletta alla milanese]]''. Before this time, the story was unknown in [[Austria]]. The Radetzky legend is however based on this book, which claims that a Count Attems, an [[adjutant]] to the emperor [[Franz Joseph I of Austria]] gave a notice from Radetzky about the situation in [[Lombardy]] and mentioned a tasty veal steak in a margin note. After Radetzky had returned, the emperor personally requested the recipe from him.<ref name=\"pohl\" />\n\nPohl relates this anecdote with the words: \"This story is scientifically meaningless, it does not cite any sources and it is not mentioned [\u2026] in the literature about Radetzky. No such Count Attems appears in any biographical work about the Austrian monarchy, which would have corresponded to this time and position.\"<ref name=\"pohl\" />\n\nPohl doubts that Wiener schnitzel came from Italy at all, with the basis that in the other \"imported dishes\" in [[Austrian cuisine]], the original concept is mentioned, even if in Germanised form, such as in [[goulash]] or [[pancake]]s, and the schnitzel does not appear even in specialised cookbooks about [[Italian cuisine]].<ref>Pohl, Heinz Dieter: [http://www1.ku-eichstaett.de/SLF/EngluVglSW/pohl1061.pdf Zur bairisch-\u00f6sterreichischen K\u00fcchensprache] (PDF)</ref>\n\nPohl hints that there had been other dishes in Austrian cuisine, before the Schnitzel, that were breaded and deep fried, such as the popular ''Backhendl'', which was first mentioned in a cookbook from 1719. The Schnitzel was then mentioned in the 19th century as ''{{lang|de|Wiener Schnitzel}}'' analogically to the ''{{lang|de|[[Wiener Backhendl]]}}''.<ref name=\"pohl\" />\n\nDocuments in the Milan archive of Saint Ambrose dated 1148 use the [[Latin]] name ''{{lang|la|lumbolos cum panitio}}'',<ref>{{cite web |title=The History of Wiener Schnitzel |url=http://kitchenproject.com/history/Schnitzel/Wienerschnitzel.htm |website=kitchenproject.com |accessdate=27 March 2014}}</ref> which can be translated as \"little chops with breadcrumbs\". This can be a hint that a dish similar to the ''{{lang|it|[[cotoletta alla milanese]]}}'' already existed at that time.\n\nIn 1887, [[Edward Frederick Knight|E. F. Knight]] wrote of a Wienerschnitzel ordered in a [[Rotterdam]] cafe, \"as far as I could make out, the lowest layer of a Wienerschnitzel consists of juicy veal steaks and slices of lemon peel; the next layer is composed of sardines; then come sliced gherkins, capers, and diverse mysteries; a delicate sauce flavours the whole, and the result is a gastronomic dream.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=The \"Falcon\" On the Baltic: A Coasting Voyage From Hammersmith to Copenhagen in a Three-Ton Yacht |first=E. F. |last=Knight |date=1888 |page=76}}</ref>\n\n== Preparation ==\n[[File:Wiener Schnitzel at restaurant Faro, Helsinki.jpg|thumb|right|Whereas the original Austrian Wiener schnitzel only includes lemon and parsley as garnishes, in the Nordic countries it is typically also garnished with a slice of anchovy and capers.<ref>Snellman.fi: [https://www.snellman.fi/fi/reseptit/wieninleike ''Wieninleike resepit ja ohje''] (in Finnish): ''Ja muualla kuin It\u00e4vallassa, saa wieninleike usein seurakseen my\u00f6s anjovista ja kapriksia, josta muodostuukin kerrassaan herkullinen yhdistelm\u00e4!'' (\"And outside Austria, the Wiener schnitzel is often accompanied by anchovy and capers which make a delicious combination!\")</ref>]]\nThe dish is prepared from veal slices, butterfly cut, about {{convert|4|mm}} thin and lightly pounded flat, slightly salted, and rolled in flour, whipped eggs, and bread crumbs. The bread crumbs must not be pressed into the meat, so that they stay dry and can be \"souffl\u00e9d\". Finally the Schnitzel is fried in a good proportion of [[lard]] or [[clarified butter]] at a temperature from 160 to 170&nbsp;\u00b0C<ref>{{cite web |title=Nur mal so: Wiener Schnitzel ist Kalbfleisch, kein Schnitzel aus dem Toaster |url=http://www.focus.de/gesundheit/ernaehrung/gesundessen/nur-mal-so-wiener-schnitzel-ist-kalbfleisch-kein-schnitzel-aus-dem-toaster-kommentar_851318.html |publisher=[[Focus (German magazine)|Focus.de]] |date=10 January 2008 |accessdate=27 March 2014 |language=German}}</ref> until it is golden yellow. The Schnitzel must swim in the fat, otherwise it will not cook evenly: the fat cools too much and intrudes into the bread crumbs, moistening them. During the frying the Schnitzel is repeatedly slightly tossed around the pan. Also during the frying, fat can be scooped from the pan with a spoon and poured onto the meat. The Schnitzel is cooked after it turns golden yellow or brown.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.germanfoodguide.com/schnitzel.cfm |title=Wiener Schnitzel \u2013 Tips for Preparing a Wiener Schnitzel |publisher=German Food Guide |accessdate=27 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe dish is traditionally served in Austria with [[Lettuce#Cultivars (varieties)|Butterhead lettuce]] tossed with a sweetened [[vinaigrette]] dressing, optionally with chopped chives or onions), [[potato salad]], cucumber salad, or parsley potatoes. Currently{{when|date=November 2019}} it is also served with rice, [[french fries]] or roasted potatoes. In earlier days, the garnish consisted of capers and [[Anchovies as food|anchovies]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hampel |first1=Friedrich - executive chef of the imperial court|title=Lucullus. Handbuch der Wiener Kochkunst |date=1915 |location=Vienna |chapter=Recipe No. 147}}</ref>, nowadays a lemon slice and parsley are more common.\n\n== Similar dishes ==\n[[File:Wiener Schnitzel vom Schwein.jpg|thumb|Pork schnitzel variation stuffed with fried mushrooms and onions (''Fuhrmann Schnitzel vom Schwein''), served with mashed potato and side salad]]\n\nA popular variation is made with [[pork]] instead of veal, because pork is cheaper than veal (usually about half the price). To avoid mixing up different products, the Austrian and German food committees have decided that a \"Wiener Schnitzel\" must be made of veal. A Schnitzel made of pork can be called \"Wiener Schnitzel vom Schwein\" (''Viennese schnitzel from pork'') or \"Schnitzel Wiener Art\" (''Viennese style schnitzel'').\n\nSimilar dishes to Wiener schnitzel include ''{{lang|de|[[Surschnitzel]]}}'' (from [[curing (food preservation)|cured]] meat), and breaded turkey or chicken steaks. Similarly prepared dishes include ''{{lang|it|[[cotoletta alla milanese]]}}'', [[Cordon bleu (dish)|schnitzel cordon bleu]] filled with [[ham]] and [[cheese]]<ref>[http://www.kulinarischeserbe.ch/product.aspx?id=131 Cordon bleu], Verein Kulinarisches Erbe der Schweiz. Accessed on 27 December 2008.</ref> and ''[[Pariser Schnitzel]]''. The American [[chicken-fried steak]] is often said to be closely related to Wiener schnitzel, the result of the adaptation of the recipe by German or Austrian immigrants to the [[Texas Hill Country]] to locally available ingredients.<ref name=\"ohs\">{{cite web  | last = Weaver  | first = Bobby  | title = Chicken-Fried Steak  | work = Oklahoma Encyclopedia of History and Culture  | publisher = Oklahoma Historical Society  | date =   | url = http://digital.library.okstate.edu/encyclopedia/entries/C/CH039.html  | accessdate = January 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[Tonkatsu]] is a similar, fried pork cutlet from [[Japanese cuisine]], is thicker than its European counterparts and widespread in Japan and South Korea.\n\nIn the [[Southern Cone]], particularly in [[Argentina]] and [[Uruguay]], a similar dish is [[milanesa]], often served with french fries or mashed potatoes.\n\nIn [[Israel]], schnitzel is extremely popular, first introduced by European Jews who immigrated to Israel during the middle decades of the twentieth century.  Due to food shortages at that time and the high cost of meat and veal, the local version was made of chicken breast, which was less expensive. To this day, Israeli schnitzel is made of chicken.<ref name=\"VG\">{{cite news |last1=Guttman |first1=Vered |title=How to Make Schnitzel Like an Israeli |url=https://www.haaretz.com/food/how-to-make-schnitzel-like-an-israeli-1.5492263 |accessdate=4 January 2020 |publisher=Haaretz |date=30 January 2017}}</ref>  Schnitzel has become so popular that it is regularly described as one of Israel's \"national dishes.\"<ref name=\"KM\">{{cite news |title=Foods of Israel: Schnitzel |url=https://forward.com/food/132482/foods-of-israel-schnitzel/ |accessdate=4 January 2020 |publisher=The Forward |date=26 October 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"FT\">{{cite news |title=Schnitzel Conquers the World |url=https://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-life-and-religion/230138/schnitzel-conquers-the-world |accessdate=4 January 2020 |publisher=Taablet Magazine |date=5 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of veal dishes]]\n\n== References ==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n'''Further reading'''\n* Haslinger, Ingrid: ''Entwicklungsstationen einiger typischer Gerichte der Wiener K\u00fcche''. In: Dannielczyk, Julia; Wasner-Peter, Isabella (ed.): ''\"Heut' mu\u00df der Tisch sich v\u00f6llig bieg'n\". Wiener K\u00fcche und ihre Kochb\u00fccher'', Mandelbaum-Verlag, vienna 2007, {{ISBN|978-3-85476-246-1}}, pp.&nbsp;11\u201348\n* Zahnhausen, Richard: ''Das Wiener Schnitzel. Struktur und Geschichte einer allt\u00e4glichen Speise. In: Wiener Geschichtsbl\u00e4tter'', issue 2/2001, pp.&nbsp;132\u2013146. {{issn|0043-5317}}.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Wiener Schnitzel}}\n* [http://www.textetage.com/fileadmin/verena/wiener.pdf Zur Geschichte des Wiener Schnitzels] {{in lang|de}}\n* [http://www.petrafoede.de/wienerschnitzel.html Zur Geschichte von Wiener Schnitzel und Costoletta alla Milanese, mit historischen Rezepten] {{in lang|de}}\n* [http://www.vienna-unwrapped.com/wiener-schnitzel.html#.UzP5u6Lm6ko Wiener Schnitzel, All About The Most Loved Food From Austria], Vienna Unwrapped\n* [http://www.smh.com.au/travel/activity/food-and-wine/crumbs-what-a-town-20130530-2ncvb.html Crumbs, what a town] \u2013 a survey by ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'' of Viennese restaurants and their Wiener Schnitzels\n\n[[Category:Austrian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Breaded cutlets]]\n[[Category:German cuisine]]\n[[Category:Veal dishes]]\n[[Category:National dishes]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the restaurant chain|Wienerschnitzel}}\n[[File:Wiener-Schnitzel02.jpg|thumb|right|Wiener schnitzel, a traditional [[Austrian cuisine|Austrian dish]]]]\n'''Wiener schnitzel''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|v|i\u02d0|n|\u0259r|_|\u02c8|\u0283|n|\u026a|t|s|\u0259l}} {{IPA-de|\u02c8vi\u02d0n\u0250 \u02c8\u0283n\u026atsl\u0329|lang}}; {{etymology|de|Wiener Schnitzel|Viennese cutlet}}), sometimes spelled '''Wienerschnitzel''', as in Switzerland,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bickel|first1=Hans|last2=Landolt|first2=Christoph|title=Duden - Schweizerhochdeutsch : W\u00f6rterbuch der Standardsprache in der deutschen Schweiz|date=2012|publisher=Dudenverlag|location=Mannheim|isbn=9783411902682|page=85|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=hGG9BQAAQBAJ&pg=PA85|language=German}}</ref> is a type of [[schnitzel]] made of a thin, [[Bread crumbs#Breading|breaded]], pan-fried [[veal]] cutlet.\n\nIt is one of the best known specialities of [[Viennese cuisine]], and one of the national dishes of [[Austria]] and its national food.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://allthingsaustria.com/wienerschnitzel/ |title=Wiener Schnitzel \u2013 Austria\u2019s National Food | website=All Things Austria |date=13 December 2010 |accessdate=27 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://honest-food.net/2012/12/21/wiener-schnitzel-recipe/ |title=Wiener Schnitzel | website=Hunter Angler Gardener Cook |date=21 December 2012 |accessdate=27 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n== History and etymology ==\n[[File:Wiener Schnitzel at Gasthaus Joainig (lightened).jpg|thumb|right|A Wiener schnitzel served at a restaurant in [[Carinthia]], Austria]]\nThe designation {{lang|de|Wiener Schnitzel}} first appeared in the 19th century, with the first known mention in a [[cookbook]] from 1831.<ref>{{cite book |last=Neudecker |first=Maria Anna |title=Allerneuestes allgemeines Kochbuch |location=Prague |date=1831}}</ref> In the popular southern German cookbook by [[Katharina Prato]], it was mentioned as {{lang|de|eingebr\u00f6selte Kalbsschnitzchen}} (roughly, 'breaded veal cutlets').<ref name=\"pohl\">{{cite book |last=Pohl |first=Heinz Dieter |title=Die \u00f6sterreichische K\u00fcchensprache. Ein Lexikon der typisch \u00f6sterreichischen kulinarischen Besonderheiten (mit sprachwissenschaftlichen Erl\u00e4uterungen) |publisher=Praesens-Verlag |location=Vienna |date=2007 |isbn=3-7069-0452-7 |pages=154-155|language=German}}<!--(''Studia interdisciplinaria \u00c6nipontana 11'')--></ref>\n\nAccording to a tale, field marshal [[Joseph Radetzky von Radetz]] brought the recipe from [[Italy]] to Vienna in 1857. In 2007, [[linguist]] [[Heinz Dieter Pohl]] could prove that this story had been invented.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rund ums Wiener Schnitzel \u2013 ein Beitrag zur Sach- und Wortgeschichte |url=http://members.chello.at/heinz.pohl/Wiener_Schnitzel.pdf |website=Heinz Pohl Personal Homepage |accessdate=18 April 2017|language=German}}</ref> According to Pohl, the dish is first mentioned in connection with Radetzky in 1869 in an Italian gastronomy book (''Guida gastronomica d'Italia''), which was published in German in 1871 as ''Italien tafelt'', and it is claimed that the story instead concerned the ''[[cotoletta alla milanese]]''. Before this time, the story was unknown in [[Austria]]. The Radetzky legend is however based on this book, which claims that a Count Attems, an [[adjutant]] to the emperor [[Franz Joseph I of Austria]] gave a notice from Radetzky about the situation in [[Lombardy]] and mentioned a tasty veal steak in a margin note. After Radetzky had returned, the emperor personally requested the recipe from him.<ref name=\"pohl\" />\n\nPohl relates this anecdote with the words: \"This story is scientifically meaningless, it does not cite any sources and it is not mentioned [\u2026] in the literature about Radetzky. No such Count Attems appears in any biographical work about the Austrian monarchy, which would have corresponded to this time and position.\"<ref name=\"pohl\" />\n\nPohl doubts that Wiener schnitzel came from Italy at all, with the basis that in the other \"imported dishes\" in [[Austrian cuisine]], the original concept is mentioned, even if in Germanised form, such as in [[goulash]] or [[pancake]]s, and the schnitzel does not appear even in specialised cookbooks about [[Italian cuisine]].<ref>Pohl, Heinz Dieter: [http://www1.ku-eichstaett.de/SLF/EngluVglSW/pohl1061.pdf Zur bairisch-\u00f6sterreichischen K\u00fcchensprache] (PDF)</ref>\n\nPohl hints that there had been other dishes in Austrian cuisine, before the Schnitzel, that were breaded and deep fried, such as the popular ''Backhendl'', which was first mentioned in a cookbook from 1719. The Schnitzel was then mentioned in the 19th century as ''{{lang|de|Wiener Schnitzel}}'' analogically to the ''{{lang|de|[[Wiener Backhendl]]}}''.<ref name=\"pohl\" />\n\nDocuments in the Milan archive of Saint Ambrose dated 1148 use the [[Latin]] name ''{{lang|la|lumbolos cum panitio}}'',<ref>{{cite web |title=The History of Wiener Schnitzel |url=http://kitchenproject.com/history/Schnitzel/Wienerschnitzel.htm |website=kitchenproject.com |accessdate=27 March 2014}}</ref> which can be translated as \"little chops with breadcrumbs\". This can be a hint that a dish similar to the ''{{lang|it|[[cotoletta alla milanese]]}}'' already existed at that time.\n\nIn 1887, [[Edward Frederick Knight|E. F. Knight]] wrote of a Wienerschnitzel ordered in a [[Rotterdam]] cafe, \"as far as I could make out, the lowest layer of a Wienerschnitzel consists of juicy veal steaks and slices of lemon peel; the next layer is composed of sardines; then come sliced gherkins, capers, and diverse mysteries; a delicate sauce flavours the whole, and the result is a gastronomic dream.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=The \"Falcon\" On the Baltic: A Coasting Voyage From Hammersmith to Copenhagen in a Three-Ton Yacht |first=E. F. |last=Knight |date=1888 |page=76}}</ref>\n\n== Preparation ==\n[[File:Wiener Schnitzel at restaurant Faro, Helsinki.jpg|thumb|right|Whereas the original Austrian Wiener schnitzel only includes lemon and parsley as garnishes, in the Nordic countries it is typically also garnished with a slice of anchovy and capers.<ref>Snellman.fi: [https://www.snellman.fi/fi/reseptit/wieninleike ''Wieninleike resepit ja ohje''] (in Finnish): ''Ja muualla kuin It\u00e4vallassa, saa wieninleike usein seurakseen my\u00f6s anjovista ja kapriksia, josta muodostuukin kerrassaan herkullinen yhdistelm\u00e4!'' (\"And outside Austria, the Wiener schnitzel is often accompanied by anchovy and capers which make a delicious combination!\")</ref>]]\nThe dish is prepared from veal slices, butterfly cut, about {{convert|4|mm}} thin and lightly pounded flat, slightly salted, and rolled in flour, whipped eggs, and bread crumbs. The bread crumbs must not be pressed into the meat, so that they stay dry and can be \"souffl\u00e9d\". Finally the Schnitzel is fried in a good proportion of [[lard]] or [[clarified butter]] at a temperature from 160 to 170&nbsp;\u00b0C<ref>{{cite web |title=Nur mal so: Wiener Schnitzel ist Kalbfleisch, kein Schnitzel aus dem Toaster |url=http://www.focus.de/gesundheit/ernaehrung/gesundessen/nur-mal-so-wiener-schnitzel-ist-kalbfleisch-kein-schnitzel-aus-dem-toaster-kommentar_851318.html |publisher=[[Focus (German magazine)|Focus.de]] |date=10 January 2008 |accessdate=27 March 2014 |language=German}}</ref> until it is golden yellow. The Schnitzel must swim in the fat, otherwise it will not cook evenly: the fat cools too much and intrudes into the bread crumbs, moistening them. During the frying the Schnitzel is repeatedly slightly tossed around the pan. Also during the frying, fat can be scooped from the pan with a spoon and poured onto the meat. The Schnitzel is cooked after it turns golden yellow or brown.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.germanfoodguide.com/schnitzel.cfm |title=Wiener Schnitzel \u2013 Tips for Preparing a Wiener Schnitzel |publisher=German Food Guide |accessdate=27 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe dish is traditionally served in Austria with [[Lettuce#Cultivars (varieties)|Butterhead lettuce]] tossed with a sweetened [[vinaigrette]] dressing, optionally with chopped chives or onions), [[potato salad]], cucumber salad, or parsley potatoes. Currently{{when|date=November 2019}} it is also served with rice, [[french fries]] or roasted potatoes. In earlier days, the garnish consisted of capers and [[Anchovies as food|anchovies]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hampel |first1=Friedrich - executive chef of the imperial court|title=Lucullus. Handbuch der Wiener Kochkunst |date=1915 |location=Vienna |chapter=Recipe No. 147}}</ref>, nowadays a lemon slice and parsley are more common.\n\n== Similar dishes ==\n[[File:Wiener Schnitzel vom Schwein.jpg|thumb|Pork schnitzel variation stuffed with fried mushrooms and onions (''Fuhrmann Schnitzel vom Schwein''), served with mashed potato and side salad]]\n\nA popular variation is made with [[pork]] instead of veal, because pork is cheaper than veal (usually about half the price). To avoid mixing up different products, the Austrian and German food committees have decided that a \"Wiener Schnitzel\" must be made of veal. A Schnitzel made of pork can be called \"Wiener Schnitzel vom Schwein\" (''Viennese schnitzel from pork'') or \"Schnitzel Wiener Art\" (''Viennese style schnitzel'').\n\nSimilar dishes to Wiener schnitzel include ''{{lang|de|[[Surschnitzel]]}}'' (from [[curing (food preservation)|cured]] meat), and breaded turkey or chicken steaks. Similarly prepared dishes include ''{{lang|it|[[cotoletta alla milanese]]}}'', [[Cordon bleu (dish)|schnitzel cordon bleu]] filled with [[ham]] and [[cheese]]<ref>[http://www.kulinarischeserbe.ch/product.aspx?id=131 Cordon bleu], Verein Kulinarisches Erbe der Schweiz. Accessed on 27 December 2008.</ref> and ''[[Pariser Schnitzel]]''. The American [[chicken-fried steak]] is often said to be closely related to Wiener schnitzel, the result of the adaptation of the recipe by German or Austrian immigrants to the [[Texas Hill Country]] to locally available ingredients.<ref name=\"ohs\">{{cite web  | last = Weaver  | first = Bobby  | title = Chicken-Fried Steak  | work = Oklahoma Encyclopedia of History and Culture  | publisher = Oklahoma Historical Society  | date =   | url = http://digital.library.okstate.edu/encyclopedia/entries/C/CH039.html  | accessdate = January 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[Tonkatsu]] is a similar, fried pork cutlet from [[Japanese cuisine]], is thicker than its European counterparts and widespread in Japan and South Korea.\n\nIn the [[Southern Cone]], particularly in [[Argentina]] and [[Uruguay]], a similar dish is [[milanesa]], often served with french fries or mashed potatoes.\n\nIn [[Israel]], schnitzel is extremely popular, first introduced by European Jews who immigrated to Israel during the middle decades of the twentieth century.  Due to food shortages at that time and the high cost of meat and veal, the local version was made of chicken breast, which was less expensive. To this day, Israeli schnitzel is made of chicken.<ref name=\"VG\">{{cite news |last1=Guttman |first1=Vered |title=How to Make Schnitzel Like an Israeli |url=https://www.haaretz.com/food/how-to-make-schnitzel-like-an-israeli-1.5492263 |accessdate=4 January 2020 |publisher=Haaretz |date=30 January 2017}}</ref>  Schnitzel has become so popular that it is regularly described as one of Israel's \"national dishes.\"<ref name=\"KM\">{{cite news |title=Foods of Israel: Schnitzel |url=https://forward.com/food/132482/foods-of-israel-schnitzel/ |accessdate=4 January 2020 |publisher=The Forward |date=26 October 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"FT\">{{cite news |title=Schnitzel Conquers the World |url=https://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-life-and-religion/230138/schnitzel-conquers-the-world |accessdate=4 January 2020 |publisher=Taablet Magazine |date=5 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of veal dishes]]\n\n== References ==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n'''Further reading'''\n* Haslinger, Ingrid: ''Entwicklungsstationen einiger typischer Gerichte der Wiener K\u00fcche''. In: Dannielczyk, Julia; Wasner-Peter, Isabella (ed.): ''\"Heut' mu\u00df der Tisch sich v\u00f6llig bieg'n\". Wiener K\u00fcche und ihre Kochb\u00fccher'', Mandelbaum-Verlag, vienna 2007, {{ISBN|978-3-85476-246-1}}, pp.&nbsp;11\u201348\n* Zahnhausen, Richard: ''Das Wiener Schnitzel. Struktur und Geschichte einer allt\u00e4glichen Speise. In: Wiener Geschichtsbl\u00e4tter'', issue 2/2001, pp.&nbsp;132\u2013146. {{issn|0043-5317}}.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons 