{"title_page": "Vasishtha", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox character\n|image=Ramabhadracharya Works - Painting in Arundhati (1994).jpg|caption=Depiction of [[Vashishtha]] with his wife Arundhati and Kamadhenu cow|spouse=[[Arundhati (Hinduism)|Arundhati]]|children=[[\u015aakti Mahar\u1e63i]]|honors=[[Maharishi]]s, [[Brahmarshi]] , Gurudev,\nRaghukul Guru|known_for=Rigvedic hymns}}\n\n'''Vashishtha''' ({{lang-sa|\u0935\u0936\u093f\u0937\u094d\u0920}}, [[IAST]]: ''{{transl|sa|va\u015bi\u1e63\u1e6dha}}'') is one of the oldest and most revered Vedic rishis.<ref>{{cite book|author=James G. Lochtefeld|title=The Illustrated Encyclopedia of Hinduism: N-Z|url=https://archive.org/details/illustratedencyc0000loch|url-access=registration|year=2002|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-8239-3180-4|page=[https://archive.org/details/illustratedencyc0000loch/page/742 742]}}</ref><ref name=\"dhavamony50\">{{cite book|author=Mariasusai Dhavamony|title=Hindu Spirituality|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=58UZWWzqglMC&pg=PA50|year=1999 |publisher=Gregorian| isbn=978-88-7652-818-7| pages=50 with footnote 63}}</ref> He is one of the [[Saptarishi]]s (seven great [[Rishis]]) of India. Vashishtha is credited as the chief author of [[Mandala 7]] of ''[[Rigveda]]''.<ref name=\"jamisonvash1681\">{{cite book|author1=Stephanie Jamison|author2=Joel Brereton|title=The Rigveda: 3-Volume Set |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fgzVAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA1681|year=2014|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-972078-1|pages=1681\u20131684}}</ref> Vashishtha and his family are mentioned in Rigvedic verse 10.167.4,{{refn|group=note|Kasyapa is mentioned in RV 9.114.2, Atri in RV 5.78.4, Bharadvaja in RV 6.25.9, Vishvamitra in RV 10.167.4, Gautama in RV 1.78.1, Jamadagni in RV 3.62.18, etc.;<ref>{{cite book|author= Gudrun B\u00fchnemann|authorlink=Gudrun B\u00fchnemann |title=P\u016bj\u0101: A Study in Sm\u0101rta Ritual|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=44bXAAAAMAAJ| year=1988| publisher=Brill Academic|isbn=978-3-900271-18-3|page=220}}</ref> Original Sanskrit text: \u092a\u094d\u0930\u0938\u0942\u0924\u094b \u092d\u0915\u094d\u0937\u092e\u0915\u0930\u0902 \u091a\u0930\u093e\u0935\u092a\u093f \u0938\u094d\u0924\u094b\u092e\u0902 \u091a\u0947\u092e\u0902 \u092a\u094d\u0930\u0925\u092e\u0903 \u0938\u0942\u0930\u093f\u0930\u0941\u0928\u094d\u092e\u0943\u091c\u0947 \u0964 \u0938\u0941\u0924\u0947 \u0938\u093e\u0924\u0947\u0928 \u092f\u0926\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0917\u092e\u0902 \u0935\u093e\u0902 \u092a\u094d\u0930\u0924\u093f '''\u0935\u093f\u0936\u094d\u0935\u093e\u092e\u093f\u0924\u094d\u0930'''\u091c\u092e\u0926\u0917\u094d\u0928\u0940 \u0926\u092e\u0947 \u0965\u096a\u0965<ref>[https://sa.wikisource.org/wiki/\u090b\u0917\u094d\u0935\u0947\u0926:_\u0938\u0942\u0915\u094d\u0924\u0902_\u0967\u0966.\u0967\u096c\u096d Rigveda 10.167.4], Wikisource</ref>}} other Rigvedic mandalas and in many Vedic texts.<ref>\"according to Rig Veda 7.33:11 he is the son of Maitravarun and Urvashi\" Prof. Shrikant Prasoon, Pustak Mahal, 2009, {{ISBN|8122310729}}, {{ISBN|9788122310726}}. [https://books.google.com/books?id=bHIpvQDlazAC&lpg=PA109]</ref><ref>{{citation|title=Rigveda|translator=Ralph T.H. Griffith|quote=A form of lustre springing from the lightning wast thou, when Varu\u1e47a and Mitra saw thee;<br>Tliy one and only birth was then, Vashi\u1e63\u1e6dha, when from thy stock [[Agastya]] brought thee hither.<br>Born of their love for Urvasi, Vashi\u1e63\u1e6dha thou, priest, art son of Varu\u1e47a and Mitra;<br> And as a fallen drop, in heavenly fervour, all the Gods laid thee on a lotus-blossom |url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv07033.htm }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Maurice Bloomfield|title=Atharvaveda |url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.180555 |year=1899|publisher=K.J. Tr\u00fcbner|pages=[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.180555/page/n35 31], 111, 126}}</ref> His ideas have been influential and he was called as the first sage of the [[Vedanta]] school of Hindu philosophy by [[Adi Shankara]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Chapple |first=Christopher |authorlink=Christopher Chapple |title=The Concise Yoga V\u0101shi\u1e63\u1e6dha |translator=[[Swami Venkatesananda|Venkatesananda, Swami]] |contribution=Introduction |publisher=State University of New York Press |location=Albany |year=1984 |isbn=0-87395-955-8 |oclc=11044869 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1FFdOj2dv8cC |p=xi}}</ref>\n\n''[[Yoga Vasistha|Yoga Vashishtha]]'', ''Vashishtha Samhita'', as well as some versions of the ''[[Agni Purana]]''<ref name=\"wilsonxxxvi\">{{cite book|author=Horace Hayman Wilson|title=The Vish\u0144u Pur\u00e1\u0144a: A System of Hindu Mythology and Tradition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=satCAAAAcAAJ|year=1840|publisher=Oriental Translation Fund of Great Britain and Ireland|page=xxxvi}}</ref> and ''[[Vishnu Purana]]'' are attributed to him. He is the subject of many mythologies, such as him being in possession of the divine cow [[Kamadhenu]] and Nandini her child, who could grant anything to their owners. He is famous in Hindu mythologies for his legendary conflicts with sage [[Vishvamitra]].<ref name=\"dhavamony50\" /><ref>{{cite book|author=Horace Hayman Wilson|title=The Vish\u0144u Pur\u00e1\u0144a: A System of Hindu Mythology and Tradition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=satCAAAAcAAJ|year=1840|publisher=Oriental Translation Fund of Great Britain and Ireland|page=lxix}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Adheesh A. Sathaye|title=Crossing the Lines of Caste: Vishvamitra and the Construction of Brahmin Power in Hindu Mythology |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Rrm6BwAAQBAJ&pg=PA254 |year=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=97Rama19-934111-5|pages=254\u2013255}}</ref> In [[Ramayana]], he was the family priest of Raghu dynasty and teacher of Lord Rama and his brothers.\n\n==Etymology==\nVashishtha is also spelled as ''{{transl|sa|Vasi\u1e63\u1e6dha}}'' and is Sanskrit for \"most excellent, best or richest. According to Monier-Williams, it is sometimes incorrectly spelt as Vashishtha or Vashistha (''{{transl|sa|va\u015bi\u1e63\u1e6dha}}'', {{lang|sa|\u0935\u0936\u093f\u0937\u094d\u0920}}).<ref>{{MWSD|va\u015bi\u1e63\u1e6dha}}, [http://www.ibiblio.org/sripedia/ebooks/mw/0900/mw__0963.html Archive 2]</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn Rigvedic hymn 7.33.9, Vashishtha is described as a scholar who moved across the [[Indus river]] to establish his school.<ref>{{cite book|author=Michael Witzel|title=Inside the Texts, Beyond the Texts: New Approaches to the Study of the Vedas: Proceedings of the International Vedic Workshop, Harvard University, June 1989 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SXHXAAAAMAAJ|year=1997|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=978-1-888789-03-4|pages=289 with footnote 145}}</ref> He was married to Arundhati, and therefore he was also called ''Arundhati Nath'', meaning the husband of Arundhati.<ref>{{cite book|title=India through the ages|last=Gopal|first=Madan|date= 1990| page= 70|editor=K.S. Gautam|publisher=Publication Division, Ministry of Information and Broadcasting, Government of India}}</ref> Vashishtha is believed to have lived on the banks of [[Ganga]] in modern-day [[Uttarakhand]]. Later, this region is believed in the Indian tradition to be the abode of sage [[Vyasa]] along with [[Pandavas]], the five brothers of [[Mahabharata]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Master's Narrative: Swami Sivananda and the Transnational Production of Yoga|jstor= 3814692|publisher=Indiana University Press|volume=23|last=Strauss|first=Sarah|journal=Journal of Folklore Research|date=2002|page=221}}</ref> He is typically described in ancient and medieval Hindu texts as a sage with long flowing hairs that are neatly tied into a bun that is coiled with a tuft to the right, a beard, a handlebar moustache and a [[tilak]] on his forehead.<ref name=\"Bryant2003p164\"/>\n\nIn Buddhist Pali canonical texts such as ''[[Digha Nikaya]]'', Tevijja Sutta describes a discussion between the Buddha and Vedic scholars of his time. The [[Buddha]] names ten [[rishi]]s, calls them \"early sages\" and makers of ancient verses that have been collected and chanted in his era, and among those ten rishi is Vasettha (the Pali spelling of Vashishtha in Sanskrit<ref>{{cite book|author=Steven Collins|title=Agga\u00f1\u00f1a Sutta|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bSI4VBQ7Y4UC&pg=PA17|year=2001|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|isbn=978-81-260-1298-5|page=17}}</ref>).<ref name=walshe188f>{{cite book|author=Maurice Walshe|title=The Long Discourses of the Buddha: A Translation of the Digha Nikaya |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Uj86AwAAQBAJ |year=2005|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-0-86171-979-2|pages=188\u2013189}}</ref>{{refn|group=note|The Buddha names the following as \"early sages\" of Vedic verses, \"Atthaka (either Ashtavakra or Atri), Vamaka, Vamadeva, Vessamitta (Visvamitra), Yamataggi, Angirasa, Bharadvaja, Vasettha (Vashistha), Kassapa (Kashyapa) and Bhagu (Bhrigu)\".<ref name=walshe188f/>}}\n\n===Ideas===\nVashishtha is the author of the seventh book of the ''[[Rigveda]]'',<ref name=jamisonvash1681/> one of its \"family books\" and among the oldest layer of hymns in the Vedic scriptures of Hinduism.<ref name=\"Witzel1997p42\"/> The hymns composed by Vashishtha are dedicated to [[Agni]], [[Indra]] and other gods, but according to RN Dandekar, in a book edited by Michael Witzel, these hymns are particularly significant for four Indravarunau hymns. These have an embedded message of transcending \"all thoughts of [[bigotry]]\",  suggesting a realistic approach of mutual \"coordination and harmony\" between two rival religious ideas by abandoning disputed ideas from each and finding the complementary spiritual core in both.<ref name=\"Witzel1997p42\">{{cite book|author=Michael Witzel|title=Inside the Texts, Beyond the Texts: New Approaches to the Study of the Vedas: Proceedings of the International Vedic Workshop, Harvard University, June 1989 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SXHXAAAAMAAJ|year=1997| publisher=Harvard University Press| isbn=978-1-888789-03-4| pages=41\u201342|oclc= 246746415}}</ref> These hymns declare two gods, [[Indra]] and [[Varuna]], as equally great. In another hymn, particularly the Rigvedic verse 8.83.9, Vashishtha teaches that the Vedic gods Indra and Varuna are complementary and equally important because one vanquishes the evil by the defeat of enemies in battles, while other sustains the good during peace through socio-ethical laws.<ref>{{cite book|author1=J. C. Heesterman|author2=Albert W. Van den Hoek|author3=Dirk H. A. Kolff |display-authors=etal|title=Ritual, State, and History in South Asia: Essays in Honour of J.C. Heesterman|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EtwtSZwyWpgC&pg=PA68|year=1992|publisher=BRILL Academic|isbn=90-04-09467-9|pages=68\u201373 with footnotes}}</ref> The seventh mandala of the ''Rigveda'' by Vashishtha is a metaphorical treatise.<ref>{{cite book|author1=J. C. Heesterman|author2=Albert W. Van den Hoek|author3=Dirk H. A. Kolff |display-authors=etal|title=Ritual, State, and History in South Asia: Essays in Honour of J.C. Heesterman|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EtwtSZwyWpgC |year=1992|publisher=BRILL Academic|isbn=90-04-09467-9|pages=136\u2013137 }}</ref> Vashishtha reappears as a character in Hindu texts, through its history, that explore conciliation between conflicting or opposing ideologies.<ref>[[Ramchandra Narayan Dandekar]] (1981), \"Vasistha as Religious Conciliator\", in ''Exercises in Indology'', Delhi: Ajanta, pages 122-132, {{oclc| 9098360}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Ellison Findly \u2013 a professor of Religion, Vashishtha hymns in the ''Rigveda'' are among the most intriguing in many ways and influential. Vashishtha emphasizes means to be as important as ends during one's life, encouraging truthfulness, devotion, optimism, family life, sharing one's prosperity with other members of society, among other cultural values.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Findly | first=Ellison Banks | title=Vasistha: Religious Personality and Vedic Culture | journal=Numen | publisher=BRILL Academic | volume=31 | issue=1 | year=1984 | pages=74\u201377, 98\u2013105 | doi=10.2307/3269890 | jstor= 3269890 | accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==Texts==\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = '''Excellence'''\n<poem>\nPractise righteousness ([[dharma]]), not unrighteousness.\nSpeak the truth, not an untruth.\nLook at what is distant, not what's near at hand.\nLook at the highest, not at what's less than highest.\n</poem>\n |source = \u2014 ''Vasishtha Dharmasutra 30.1'' {{sfn|Olivelle|1999|p=325}}\n |bgcolor=#FFE0BB\n |align  = right\n}}\n[[File:Vasistha curses Kaikeyi.jpg|thumb|Vashishtha curses Kaikeyi]]\nVasishtha is a revered sage in the Hindu traditions, and like other revered sages, numerous treatises composed in ancient and medieval era are reverentially named after him.{{Sfn|Olivelle|1999|p=xxvi}} Some treatises named after him or attributed to him include:\n* ''Vashishtha samhita'' is a medieval era [[Yoga]] text.<ref>{{cite book|title=Va\u015bi\u1e63\u1e6dha Sa\u1e43hit\u0101: Yoga k\u0101\u1e47\u1e0da|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JiuePAAACAAJ|year=2005|publisher=Kaivalyadhama S.M.Y.M. samiti|isbn=978-81-89485-37-5}}</ref> There is an [[Agama (Hinduism)|Agama]] as well with the same title.\n* ''Vashishtha [[dharmasutra]]'', an ancient text, and one of the few [[Dharma]]-related treatises which has survived into the modern era. This Dharmas\u016btra (300\u2013100 BCE) forms an independent text and other parts of the Kalpas\u016btra, that is Shrauta- and Grihya-sutras are missing.{{Sfn|Robert Lingat|1973|p=18}} It contains 1,038 sutras.{{Sfn|Patrick Olivelle |2006|page=185}}\n* ''[[Yoga Vasistha|Yoga Vashishtha]]'' is a syncretic medieval era text that presents [[Vedanta]] and [[Yoga]] philosophies. It is written in the form of a dialogue between Vashishtha and prince Rama of ''[[Ramayana]]'' fame, about the nature of life, human suffering, choices as the nature of life, free will, human creative power and spiritual liberation.<ref name=\"Chapple1984-xii\">{{Harvnb|Chapple|1984|pp=xi-xii}}</ref><ref>Surendranath Dasgupta, A History of Indian Philosophy, Volume 2, Cambridge University Press, {{ISBN|978-0521047791}}, pages 252-253</ref> Yoga Vashishtha teachings are structured as stories and fables,<ref>{{cite book |last= Venkatesananda |first=S (Translator) |title=The Concise Yoga V\u0101si\u1e63\u1e6dha |publisher=State University of New York Press |location=Albany |year=1984 |isbn=0-87395-955-8|pages=51, 77, 87, 121, 147, 180, 188, 306, 315, 354, 410}}</ref> with a philosophical foundation similar to those found in [[Advaita Vedanta]].<ref name=chappleixf>{{Harvnb|Chapple|1984|pp=ix-x with footnote 3}}</ref><ref name=aiyer5>KN Aiyer (1975), Laghu Yoga Vasishta, Theosophical Publishing House, Original Author: Abhinanda, {{ISBN|978-0835674973}}, page 5</ref><ref name=\"Leslie2003-104\">{{Harvnb|Leslie|2003|pp=104}}</ref> The text is also notable for its discussion of [[Yoga]].<ref>G Watts Cunningham (1948), [https://www.jstor.org/stable/2181797 How Far to the Land of Yoga? An Experiment in Understanding], The Philosophical Review, Vol. 57, No. 6, pages 573-589</ref><ref>F Chenet (1987), Bh\u0101van\u0101 et Cr\u00e9ativit\u00e9 de la Conscience, Numen, Vol. 34, Fasc. 1, pages 45-96 (in French)</ref> According to Christopher Chapple \u2013 a professor of Indic studies specializing in Yoga and Indian religions, the ''Yoga Vashishtha'' philosophy can be summarized as, \"Human effort can be used for self-betterment and that there is no such thing as an external fate imposed by the gods\".<ref>{{Harvnb|Chapple|1984|pp=x-xi with footnote 4}}</ref>\n*''[[Agni Purana]]'' is attributed to Vashishtha.<ref name=wilsonxxxvi/>\n*''[[Vishnu Purana]]'' is attributed to Vashishtha along with Rishi Pulatsya. He has also contributed to many Vedic hymns and is seen as the arranger of [[Vedas]] during [[Dwapara Yuga]].\n\n==Mythology==\n[[File:Vashistar1.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|A Vashishtha statue in granite stone.]]\nAccording to one of Swami Kutasthanandji pravachans the story is:\n\nIt is a story from puranik Katha about Moha. It says that nobody is free from Moha. It is bound to be there, but with little patience and understanding we can face it. Do not let this Moha become a permanent guest in your house.\n\nThere used to be very big saint, Guru Vashishtah. He was a brahmgyani. He used to teach Lord Rama by saying that this world is dream, nothing is permanent on this earth only brahm is true.\n\nVashishta had hundred sons. He was very attached to them. Once Vishwamitra, who was very egoistic, killed his hundred sons in anger. Vashistha became very sad and and depressive because he was entangled in the moha of his children. He being a saint could not bear this pain. He became very depressive and wanted to commit suicide. He went and jumped into a river. The river saw such a saint and gyani person has jumped into the river, she threw him out of the river by force. He attempted to jump again, the river just threw him out again. Brahm Rishi Vashishtha felt that he may be too light to drown so he tied himself with a stone to commit suicide by jumping in the river.\n\nThe river knew that he is a big saint and tried to help him. So she turned into a woman and stopped him from doing so. She caught hold of him and brought him near the bank of the river. She asked him why is he committing suicide. Vashishta explained to her that how Vishwamitra killed his hundred sons and because of that he does not want to live. Best is to die. The river said \"You are such a gyani purush, you have given knowledge to Lord Rama about Brahm by saying the world is not real,it is a dream and now you are finding it real, you are blinded by moha of your sons and want to destroy your life. What is the use of this gyan.\nThe river then said that you are highly knowledgeable person, highly regarded and respected by all, were going to commit such a grave sin, such a shameful act. What example would you set for your disciplines and the next generation. You have given spiritual knowledge to your disciples by saying that \"we are not body, we not mind, we are not intellect, we are not thoughts and we are just souls, the children of Almighty. How can you think of such an act\". There was continuous discussions between Rishi Vashishtha and the river who was in form of a woman. Within few minutes Rishi Vashishtha realised his mistake and came back to his original self. He regained knowledge which was covered by the thin curtain of Moha(attachment). Moha got vanished and Vashishtah realised that he is not a body, he is a soul.\nThe bondage of Moha is very strong. We cannot easily eradicate it. Even big Rishia, Munis get affected. We as normal being should not think that being attached is not a gyani bakht's quality. It is with the help of our well wisher we can overcome this Moha. This all happens with the blessings of God who helps us at the time of grief and sorrow and keeps us away from the feeling of depression.\n\nAccording to Agarwal, one mythical legend states that Vashishtha wanted to commit suicide by falling into river [[Sarasvati|Saraswati]]. But the river prevented this sacrilege by splitting into hundreds of shallow channels. This story, states Agarwal, may have very ancient roots, where \"the early man observed the braiding process of the Satluj\" and because such a legend could not have invented without the residents observing an ancient river (in Rajasthan) drying up and its tributaries such as Sutlej reflowing to merge into Indus river.<ref>{{cite web|title=Legends as models of Science|jstor=42930266|date=1990|volume=49|pages=41\u201342|last=Agarwal|first= D.P.|journal= Bulletin of the Deccan College Research Institute}}{{Subscription required|url= http://www.indianscience.org/essays/t_es_agarw_legends.shtml}}</ref>\n\n===Rivalry with Vishwamitra===\nVashishtha is known for his feud with Vishwamitra. The king Vishwamitra coveted Vashistha's divine cow Nandini that could fulfil material desires. Vashishtha destroyed Vishwamitra's army and sons. Vishwamitra acquired weapons from Lord Shiva and incinerated Vashishtha's hermitage and sons, but Vashistha baffled all of Vishwamitra's weapons. Vishwamitra betook severe penances for thousands of years and became a Brahmarshi. He even reconciled with Vashishtha.\n\n===Disciples===\nVashishtha is best known as the priest and preceptor, teacher of the Ikshvaku kings clan. He was also the preceptor of Manu, the progenitor of Kshatriyas and Ikshvaku's father. Other characters like Nahusha, Rantideva, lord Rama and Bhishma were his disciples.\n\nWhen the Bharata king Samvarta lost his kingdom to the Panchalas, he became the disciple of Vashistha. Under Vashistha's guidance, Samvarta regained his kingdom and became the ruler of the earth.\n\n==The ''Vashishtha Head''==\n\nA copper casting of a human head styled in the manner described for Vashishtha was discovered in 1958 in Delhi. This piece has been dated to around 3700 BCE, plus minus 800 years, in three western universities (ETH Zurich, Stanford and UC) using among other methods carbon-14 dating tests, spectrographic analysis, [[X-ray]] dispersal analysis and [[metallography]].<ref name=\"Bryant2003p164\"/><ref>Harry Hicks and Robert Anderson (1990), [http://www.jies.org/docs/jies_index/Vol18.html Analysis of an Indo-European Vedic Aryan Head \u2013 4500-2500 B.C.], in ''Journal of Indo European studies'', Vol. 18, pp 425\u2013446. Fall 1990.</ref> This piece is called \"Vashishtha head\", because the features, hairstyle, [[tilak]] and other features of the casting resembles the description for Vashishtha in Hindu texts.<ref name=\"Bryant2003p164\">{{cite book|author=Edwin Bryant|title=The Quest for the Origins of Vedic Culture: The Indo-Aryan Migration Debate |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y2jfHlinW4UC&pg=PA164 |year=2003|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-516947-8|page=164}}</ref>\n\nThe significance of \"Vasishtha head\" is unclear because it was not found at an archaeological site, but in open Delhi market where it was scheduled to be remelted. Further, the head had an inscription of \"Narayana\" suggesting that the item was produced in a much later millennium. The item, states Edwin Bryant, likely was re-cast and produced from an ancient pre-2800 BCE copper item that left significant traces of matter with the observed C-14 dating.<ref name=\"Bryant2003p164\"/>\n\n== Vashishtha Temples==\n[[Image:Vashisht temple.jpg|thumb|250px|Vashishtha Temple, in [[Vashisht (Village)|Vashisht]] village, [[Himachal Pradesh]]]]\n\nThere is an Ashram dedicated to Vashishtha in [[Guwahati]], [[India]]. This Ashram is situated close to [[Assam]]-[[Meghalaya]] border to the south of [[Guwahati]] city and is a major tourist attraction of Guwahati. Vashishtha's Temple is situated in [[Vashisht (Village)|Vashisht]] village, Himachal Pradesh. Vashishtha Cave, a cave on the banks of [[Ganges]] at Shivpuri, 18&nbsp;km from [[Rishikesh]] is also locally believed to be his winter abode and houses a Shiva temple, also nearby is Arundhati Cave.\n\nGuru Vashishtha is also the primary deity at [[Arattupuzha Temple]] known as Arattupuzha Sree Dharmasastha in [[Arattupuzha]] village in [[Thrissur]] district of [[Kerala]]. The famous [[Arattupuzha Pooram]] is a yearly celebration where Sri Rama comes from the [[Thriprayar Temple]] to pay obeisance to his Guru at Arattupuzha temple.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Agastya]]\n* [[Aruni]]\n* [[Atri]]\n* [[Kashyapa]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\nhttp://kutasthanandji.blogspot.com/?m=1\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book |last=Chapple |first=Christopher |authorlink=Christopher Chapple |title=The Concise Yoga V\u0101si\u1e63\u1e6dha |translator=[[Swami Venkatesananda|Venkatesananda, Swami]] |contribution=Introduction |publisher=State University of New York Press |location=Albany |year=1984 |isbn=0-87395-955-8 |oclc=11044869 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1FFdOj2dv8cC |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=Robert Lingat |title=The Classical Law of India |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Sauo8iSIj7YC |year=1973 |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=978-0-520-01898-3 }}\n* {{citation |first=Patrick|last= Olivelle|title=Dharmasutras: The Law Codes of Ancient India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gnVxqvPg9a0C|year=1999|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-283882-7 }}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=Patrick Olivelle |title=Between the Empires: Society in India 300 BCE to 400 CE |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=efaOR_-YsIcC |year=2006|publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-977507-1 }}\n*{{cite book |title=The Philosophy of the Yoga Vashista. A Comparative Critical and Synthetic Survey of the Philosophical Ideas of Vashista as presented in the Yoga-Vashista Maha-Ramayan. Based on a thesis approved for the degree of Doctor of Letters in the Banaras Hindu University |publisher=Darshana Printers |location=Moradabad |first=B L |last=Atreya |date=1981|origyear= 1935) |page=467}}\n* {{Cite book |last = Leslie |first = Julia |year = 2003 |title = Authority and meaning in Indian religions: Hinduism and the case of V\u0101lm\u012bki |publisher = Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.  |isbn = 0-7546-3431-0 |url = https://archive.org/details/authoritymeaning00lesl  |url-access = registration |ref = harv }}\n*{{cite book |title=The Vision and the Way of Vashista |publisher=Indian Heritage Trust |location=Madras |first=B L |last=Atreya |date=1993 |oclc=30508760 |page=583}} Selected verses, sorted by subject, in both Sanskrit and English text.\n*{{cite book |title=The Essence of Yogavaasishtha |publisher=Samata Books |location=Chennai |author=V\u0101lm\u012bki |others=Compiled by Sri Jnanananda Bharati, transl. by Samvid |origyear=1982|date=2002 |pages=344}} Sanskrit and English text.\n*{{cite book |title=Yoga Vashista Sara: The Essence of Yoga Vashista |publisher=Sri Ramanasramam |location=Tiruvannamalai |author=V\u0101lm\u012bki |others=trans. Swami Sur\u0113\u015b\u0101nanda |date=1976 |oclc=10560384 |pages=29}} Very short condensation.\n\n{{Rishis of Hindu mythology}}\n{{HinduMythology}}\n{{Rigveda}}\n{{Ramayana}}\n\n[[Category:Hindu sages]]\n[[Category:Indian astrologers]]\n[[Category:Ancient Indian astronomers]]\n[[Category:Ancient astrologers]]\n[[Category:Prajapatis]]\n[[Category:Brahmin gotras]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox character\n|image=Ramabhadracharya Works - Painting in Arundhati (1994).jpg|caption=Depiction of [[Vashishtha]] with his wife Arundhati and Kamadhenu cow|spouse=[[Arundhati (Hinduism)|Arundhati]]|children=[[\u015aakti Mahar\u1e63i]]|honors=[[Maharishi]]s, [[Brahmarshi]] , Gurudev,\nRaghukul Guru|known_for=Rigvedic hymns}}\n\n'''Vashishtha''' ({{lang-sa|\u0935\u0936\u093f\u0937\u094d\u0920}}, [[IAST]]: ''{{transl|sa|va\u015bi\u1e63\u1e6dha}}'') is one of the oldest and most revered Vedic rishis.<ref>{{cite book|author=James G. Lochtefeld|title=The Illustrated Encyclopedia of Hinduism: N-Z|url=https://archive.org/details/illustratedencyc0000loch|url-access=registration|year=2002|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-8239-3180-4|page=[https://archive.org/details/illustratedencyc0000loch/page/742 742]}}</ref><ref name=\"dhavamony50\">{{cite book|author=Mariasusai Dhavamony|title=Hindu Spirituality|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=58UZWWzqglMC&pg=PA50|year=1999 |publisher=Gregorian| isbn=978-88-7652-818-7| pages=50 with footnote 63}}</ref> He is one of the [[Saptarishi]]s (seven great [[Rishis]]) of India. Vashishtha is credited as the chief author of [[Mandala 7]] of ''[[Rigveda]]''.<ref name=\"jamisonvash1681\">{{cite book|author1=Stephanie Jamison|author2=Joel Brereton|title=The Rigveda: 3-Volume Set |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fgzVAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA1681|year=2014|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-972078-1|pages=1681\u20131684}}</ref> Vashishtha and his family are mentioned in Rigvedic verse 10.167.4,{{refn|group=note|Kasyapa is mentioned in RV 9.114.2, Atri in RV 5.78.4, Bharadvaja in RV 6.25.9, Vishvamitra in RV 10.167.4, Gautama in RV 1.78.1, Jamadagni in RV 3.62.18, etc.;<ref>{{cite book|author= Gudrun B\u00fchnemann|authorlink=Gudrun B\u00fchnemann |title=P\u016bj\u0101: A Study in Sm\u0101rta Ritual|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=44bXAAAAMAAJ| year=1988| publisher=Brill Academic|isbn=978-3-900271-18-3|page=220}}</ref> Original Sanskrit text: \u092a\u094d\u0930\u0938\u0942\u0924\u094b \u092d\u0915\u094d\u0937\u092e\u0915\u0930\u0902 \u091a\u0930\u093e\u0935\u092a\u093f \u0938\u094d\u0924\u094b\u092e\u0902 \u091a\u0947\u092e\u0902 \u092a\u094d\u0930\u0925\u092e\u0903 \u0938\u0942\u0930\u093f\u0930\u0941\u0928\u094d\u092e\u0943\u091c\u0947 \u0964 \u0938\u0941\u0924\u0947 \u0938\u093e\u0924\u0947\u0928 \u092f\u0926\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0917\u092e\u0902 \u0935\u093e\u0902 \u092a\u094d\u0930\u0924\u093f '''\u0935\u093f\u0936\u094d\u0935\u093e\u092e\u093f\u0924\u094d\u0930'''\u091c\u092e\u0926\u0917\u094d\u0928\u0940 \u0926\u092e\u0947 \u0965\u096a\u0965<ref>[https://sa.wikisource.org/wiki/\u090b\u0917\u094d\u0935\u0947\u0926:_\u0938\u0942\u0915\u094d\u0924\u0902_\u0967\u0966.\u0967\u096c\u096d Rigveda 10.167.4], Wikisource</ref>}} other Rigvedic mandalas and in many Vedic texts.<ref>\"according to Rig Veda 7.33:11 he is the son of Maitravarun and Urvashi\" Prof. Shrikant Prasoon, Pustak Mahal, 2009, {{ISBN|8122310729}}, {{ISBN|9788122310726}}. [https://books.google.com/books?id=bHIpvQDlazAC&lpg=PA109]</ref><ref>{{citation|title=Rigveda|translator=Ralph T.H. Griffith|quote=A form of lustre springing from the lightning wast thou, when Varu\u1e47a and Mitra saw thee;<br>Tliy one and only birth was then, Vashi\u1e63\u1e6dha, when from thy stock [[Agastya]] brought thee hither.<br>Born of their love for Urvasi, Vashi\u1e63\u1e6dha thou, priest, art son of Varu\u1e47a and Mitra;<br> And as a fallen drop, in heavenly fervour, all the Gods laid thee on a lotus-blossom |url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/rigveda/rv07033.htm }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Maurice Bloomfield|title=Atharvaveda |url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.180555 |year=1899|publisher=K.J. Tr\u00fcbner|pages=[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.180555/page/n35 31], 111, 126}}</ref> His ideas have been influential and he was called as the first sage of the [[Vedanta]] school of Hindu philosophy by [[Adi Shankara]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Chapple |first=Christopher |authorlink=Christopher Chapple |title=The Concise Yoga V\u0101shi\u1e63\u1e6dha |translator=[[Swami Venkatesananda|Venkatesananda, Swami]] |contribution=Introduction |publisher=State University of New York Press |location=Albany |year=1984 |isbn=0-87395-955-8 |oclc=11044869 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1FFdOj2dv8cC |p=xi}}</ref>\n\n''[[Yoga Vasistha|Yoga Vashishtha]]'', ''Vashishtha Samhita'', as well as some versions of the ''[[Agni Purana]]''<ref name=\"wilsonxxxvi\">{{cite book|author=Horace Hayman Wilson|title=The Vish\u0144u Pur\u00e1\u0144a: A System of Hindu Mythology and Tradition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=satCAAAAcAAJ|year=1840|publisher=Oriental Translation Fund of Great Britain and Ireland|page=xxxvi}}</ref> and ''[[Vishnu Purana]]'' are attributed to him. He is the subject of many mythologies, such as him being in possession of the divine cow [[Kamadhenu]] and Nandini her child, who could grant anything to their owners. He is famous in Hindu mythologies for his legendary conflicts with sage [[Vishvamitra]].<ref name=\"dhavamony50\" /><ref>{{cite book|author=Horace Hayman Wilson|title=The Vish\u0144u Pur\u00e1\u0144a: A System of Hindu Mythology and Tradition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=satCAAAAcAAJ|year=1840|publisher=Oriental Translation Fund of Great Britain and Ireland|page=lxix}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Adheesh A. Sathaye|title=Crossing the Lines of Caste: Vishvamitra and the Construction of Brahmin Power in Hindu Mythology |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Rrm6BwAAQBAJ&pg=PA254 |year=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=97Rama19-934111-5|pages=254\u2013255}}</ref> In [[Ramayana]], he was the family priest of Raghu dynasty and teacher of Lord Rama and his brothers.\n\n==Etymology==\nVashishtha is also spelled as ''{{transl|sa|Vasi\u1e63\u1e6dha}}'' and is Sanskrit for \"most excellent, best or richest. According to Monier-Williams, it is sometimes incorrectly spelt as Vashishtha or Vashistha (''{{transl|sa|va\u015bi\u1e63\u1e6dha}}'', {{lang|sa|\u0935\u0936\u093f\u0937\u094d\u0920}}).<ref>{{MWSD|va\u015bi\u1e63\u1e6dha}}, [http://www.ibiblio.org/sripedia/ebooks/mw/0900/mw__0963.html Archive 2]</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn Rigvedic hymn 7.33.9, Vashishtha is described as a scholar who moved across the [[Indus river]] to establish his school.<ref>{{cite book|author=Michael Witzel|title=Inside the Texts, Beyond the Texts: New Approaches to the Study of the Vedas: Proceedings of the International Vedic Workshop, Harvard University, June 1989 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SXHXAAAAMAAJ|year=1997|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=978-1-888789-03-4|pages=289 with footnote 145}}</ref> He was married to Arundhati, and therefore he was also called ''Arundhati Nath'', meaning the husband of Arundhati.<ref>{{cite book|title=India through the ages|last=Gopal|first=Madan|date= 1990| page= 70|editor=K.S. Gautam|publisher=Publication Division, Ministry of Information and Broadcasting, Government of India}}</ref> Vashishtha is believed to have lived on the banks of [[Ganga]] in modern-day [[Uttarakhand]]. Later, this region is believed in the Indian tradition to be the abode of sage [[Vyasa]] along with [[Pandavas]], the five brothers of [[Mahabharata]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Master's Narrative: Swami Sivananda and the Transnational Production of Yoga|jstor= 3814692|publisher=Indiana University Press|volume=23|last=Strauss|first=Sarah|journal=Journal of Folklore Research|date=2002|page=221}}</ref> He is typically described in ancient and medieval Hindu texts as a sage with long flowing hairs that are neatly tied into a bun that is coiled with a tuft to the right, a beard, a handlebar moustache and a [[tilak]] on his forehead.<ref name=\"Bryant2003p164\"/>\n\nIn Buddhist Pali canonical texts such as ''[[Digha Nikaya]]'', Tevijja Sutta describes a discussion between the Buddha and Vedic scholars of his time. The [[Buddha]] names ten [[rishi]]s, calls them \"early sages\" and makers of ancient verses that have been collected and chanted in his era, and among those ten rishi is Vasettha (the Pali spelling of Vashishtha in Sanskrit<ref>{{cite book|author=Steven Collins|title=Agga\u00f1\u00f1a Sutta|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bSI4VBQ7Y4UC&pg=PA17|year=2001|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|isbn=978-81-260-1298-5|page=17}}</ref>).<ref name=walshe188f>{{cite book|author=Maurice Walshe|title=The Long Discourses of the Buddha: A Translation of the Digha Nikaya |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Uj86AwAAQBAJ |year=2005|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-0-86171-979-2|pages=188\u2013189}}</ref>{{refn|group=note|The Buddha names the following as \"early sages\" of Vedic verses, \"Atthaka (either Ashtavakra or Atri), Vamaka, Vamadeva, Vessamitta (Visvamitra), Yamataggi, Angirasa, Bharadvaja, Vasettha (Vashistha), Kassapa (Kashyapa) and Bhagu (Bhrigu)\".<ref name=walshe188f/>}}\n\n===Ideas===\nVashishtha is the author of the seventh book of the ''[[Rigveda]]'',<ref name=jamisonvash1681/> one of its \"family books\" and among the oldest layer of hymns in the Vedic scriptures of Hinduism.<ref name=\"Witzel1997p42\"/> The hymns composed by Vashishtha are dedicated to [[Agni]], [[Indra]] and other gods, but according to RN Dandekar, in a book edited by Michael Witzel, these hymns are particularly significant for four Indravarunau hymns. These have an embedded message of transcending \"all thoughts of [[bigotry]]\",  suggesting a realistic approach of mutual \"coordination and harmony\" between two rival religious ideas by abandoning disputed ideas from each and finding the complementary spiritual core in both.<ref name=\"Witzel1997p42\">{{cite book|author=Michael Witzel|title=Inside the Texts, Beyond the Texts: New Approaches to the Study of the Vedas: Proceedings of the International Vedic Workshop, Harvard University, June 1989 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SXHXAAAAMAAJ|year=1997| publisher=Harvard University Press| isbn=978-1-888789-03-4| pages=41\u201342|oclc= 246746415}}</ref> These hymns declare two gods, [[Indra]] and [[Varuna]], as equally great. In another hymn, particularly the Rigvedic verse 8.83.9, Vashishtha teaches that the Vedic gods Indra and Varuna are complementary and equally important because one vanquishes the evil by the defeat of enemies in battles, while other sustains the good during peace through socio-ethical laws.<ref>{{cite book|author1=J. C. Heesterman|author2=Albert W. Van den Hoek|author3=Dirk H. A. Kolff |display-authors=etal|title=Ritual, State, and History in South Asia: Essays in Honour of J.C. Heesterman|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EtwtSZwyWpgC&pg=PA68|year=1992|publisher=BRILL Academic|isbn=90-04-09467-9|pages=68\u201373 with footnotes}}</ref> The seventh mandala of the ''Rigveda'' by Vashishtha is a metaphorical treatise.<ref>{{cite book|author1=J. C. Heesterman|author2=Albert W. Van den Hoek|author3=Dirk H. A. Kolff |display-authors=etal|title=Ritual, State, and History in South Asia: Essays in Honour of J.C. Heesterman|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EtwtSZwyWpgC |year=1992|publisher=BRILL Academic|isbn=90-04-09467-9|pages=136\u2013137 }}</ref> Vashishtha reappears as a character in Hindu texts, through its history, that explore conciliation between conflicting or opposing ideologies.<ref>[[Ramchandra Narayan Dandekar]] (1981), \"Vasistha as Religious Conciliator\", in ''Exercises in Indology'', Delhi: Ajanta, pages 122-132, {{oclc| 9098360}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Ellison Findly \u2013 a professor of Religion, Vashishtha hymns in the ''Rigveda'' are among the most intriguing in many ways and influential. Vashishtha emphasizes means to be as important as ends during one's life, encouraging truthfulness, devotion, optimism, family life, sharing one's prosperity with other members of society, among other cultural values.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Findly | first=Ellison Banks | title=Vasistha: Religious Personality and Vedic Culture | journal=Numen | publisher=BRILL Academic | volume=31 | issue=1 | year=1984 | pages=74\u201377, 98\u2013105 | doi=10.2307/3269890 | jstor= 3269890 | accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==Texts==\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = '''Excellence'''\n<poem>\nPractise righteousness ([[dharma]]), not unrighteousness.\nSpeak the truth, not an untruth.\nLook at what is distant, not what's near at hand.\nLook at the highest, not at what's less than highest.\n</poem>\n |source = \u2014 ''Vasishtha Dharmasutra 30.1'' {{sfn|Olivelle|1999|p=325}}\n |bgcolor=#FFE0BB\n |align  = right\n}}\n[[File:Vasistha curses Kaikeyi.jpg|thumb|Vashishtha curses Kaikeyi]]\nVasishtha is a revered sage in the Hindu traditions, and like other revered sages, numerous treatises composed in ancient and medieval era are reverentially named after him.{{Sfn|Olivelle|1999|p=xxvi}} Some treatises named after him or attributed to him include:\n* ''Vashishtha samhita'' is a medieval era [[Yoga]] text.<ref>{{cite book|title=Va\u015bi\u1e63\u1e6dha Sa\u1e43hit\u0101: Yoga k\u0101\u1e47\u1e0da|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JiuePAAACAAJ|year=2005|publisher=Kaivalyadhama S.M.Y.M. samiti|isbn=978-81-89485-37-5}}</ref> There is an [[Agama (Hinduism)|Agama]] as well with the same title.\n* ''Vashishtha [[dharmasutra]]'', an ancient text, and one of the few [[Dharma]]-related treatises which has survived into the modern era. This Dharmas\u016btra (300\u2013100 BCE) forms an independent text and other parts of the Kalpas\u016btra, that is Shrauta- and Grihya-sutras are missing.{{Sfn|Robert Lingat|1973|p=18}} It contains 1,038 sutras.{{Sfn|Patrick Olivelle |2006|page=185}}\n* ''[[Yoga Vasistha|Yoga Vashishtha]]'' is a syncretic medieval era text that presents [[Vedanta]] and [[Yoga]] philosophies. It is written in the form of a dialogue between Vashishtha and prince Rama of ''[[Ramayana]]'' fame, about the nature of life, human suffering, choices as the nature of life, free will, human creative power and spiritual liberation.<ref name=\"Chapple1984-xii\">{{Harvnb|Chapple|1984|pp=xi-xii}}</ref><ref>Surendranath Dasgupta, A History of Indian Philosophy, Volume 2, Cambridge University Press, {{ISBN|978-0521047791}}, pages 252-253</ref> Yoga Vashishtha teachings are structured as stories and fables,<ref>{{cite book |last= Venkatesananda |first=S (Translator) |title=The Concise Yoga V\u0101si\u1e63\u1e6dha |publisher=State University of New York Press |location=Albany |year=1984 |isbn=0-87395-955-8|pages=51, 77, 87, 121, 147, 180, 188, 306, 315, 354, 410}}</ref> with a philosophical foundation similar to those found in [[Advaita Vedanta]].<ref name=chappleixf>{{Harvnb|Chapple|1984|pp=ix-x with footnote 3}}</ref><ref name=aiyer5>KN Aiyer (1975), Laghu Yoga Vasishta, Theosophical Publishing House, Original Author: Abhinanda, {{ISBN|978-0835674973}}, page 5</ref><ref name=\"Leslie2003-104\">{{Harvnb|Leslie|2003|pp=104}}</ref> The text is also notable for its discussion of [[Yoga]].<ref>G Watts Cunningham (1948), [https://www.jstor.org/stable/2181797 How Far to the Land of Yoga? An Experiment in Understanding], The Philosophical Review, Vol. 57, No. 6, pages 573-589</ref><ref>F Chenet (1987), Bh\u0101van\u0101 et Cr\u00e9ativit\u00e9 de la Conscience, Numen, Vol. 34, Fasc. 1, pages 45-96 (in French)</ref> According to Christopher Chapple \u2013 a professor of Indic studies specializing in Yoga and Indian religions, the ''Yoga Vashishtha'' philosophy can be summarized as, \"Human effort can be used for self-betterment and that there is no such thing as an external fate imposed by the gods\".<ref>{{Harvnb|Chapple|1984|pp=x-xi with footnote 4}}</ref>\n*''[[Agni Purana]]'' is attributed to Vashishtha.<ref name=wilsonxxxvi/>\n*''[[Vishnu Purana]]'' is attributed to Vashishtha along with Rishi Pulatsya. He has also contributed to many Vedic hymns and is seen as the arranger of [[Vedas]] during [[Dwapara Yuga]].\n\n==Mythology==\n[[File:Vashistar1.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|A Vashishtha statue in granite stone.]]\nAccording to Agarwal, one mythical legend states that Vashishtha wanted to commit suicide by falling into river [[Sarasvati|Saraswati]]. But the river prevented this sacrilege by splitting into hundreds of shallow channels. This story, states Agarwal, may have very ancient roots, where \"the early man observed the braiding process of the Satluj\" and because such a legend could not have invented without the residents observing an ancient river (in Rajasthan) drying up and its tributaries such as Sutlej reflowing to merge into Indus river.<ref>{{cite web|title=Legends as models of Science|jstor=42930266|date=1990|volume=49|pages=41\u201342|last=Agarwal|first= D.P.|journal= Bulletin of the Deccan College Research Institute}}{{Subscription required|url= http://www.indianscience.org/essays/t_es_agarw_legends.shtml}}</ref>\n\n===Rivalry with Vishwamitra===\nVashishtha is known for his feud with Vishwamitra. The king Vishwamitra coveted Vashistha's divine cow Nandini that could fulfil material desires. Vashishtha destroyed Vishwamitra's army and sons. Vishwamitra acquired weapons from Lord Shiva and incinerated Vashishtha's hermitage and sons, but Vashistha baffled all of Vishwamitra's weapons. Vishwamitra betook severe penances for thousands of years and became a Brahmarshi. He even reconciled with Vashishtha.\n\n===Disciples===\nVashishtha is best known as the priest and preceptor, teacher of the Ikshvaku kings clan. He was also the preceptor of Manu, the progenitor of Kshatriyas and Ikshvaku's father. Other characters like Nahusha, Rantideva, lord Rama and Bhishma were his disciples.\n\nWhen the Bharata king Samvarta lost his kingdom to the Panchalas, he became the disciple of Vashistha. Under Vashistha's guidance, Samvarta regained his kingdom and became the ruler of the earth.\n\n==The ''Vashishtha Head''==\n\nA copper casting of a human head styled in the manner described for Vashishtha was discovered in 1958 in Delhi. This piece has been dated to around 3700 BCE, plus minus 800 years, in three western universities (ETH Zurich, Stanford and UC) using among other methods carbon-14 dating tests, spectrographic analysis, [[X-ray]] dispersal analysis and [[metallography]].<ref name=\"Bryant2003p164\"/><ref>Harry Hicks and Robert Anderson (1990), [http://www.jies.org/docs/jies_index/Vol18.html Analysis of an Indo-European Vedic Aryan Head \u2013 4500-2500 B.C.], in ''Journal of Indo European studies'', Vol. 18, pp 425\u2013446. Fall 1990.</ref> This piece is called \"Vashishtha head\", because the features, hairstyle, [[tilak]] and other features of the casting resembles the description for Vashishtha in Hindu texts.<ref name=\"Bryant2003p164\">{{cite book|author=Edwin Bryant|title=The Quest for the Origins of Vedic Culture: The Indo-Aryan Migration Debate |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y2jfHlinW4UC&pg=PA164 |year=2003|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-516947-8|page=164}}</ref>\n\nThe significance of \"Vasishtha head\" is unclear because it was not found at an archaeological site, but in open Delhi market where it was scheduled to be remelted. Further, the head had an inscription of \"Narayana\" suggesting that the item was produced in a much later millennium. The item, states Edwin Bryant, likely was re-cast and produced from an ancient pre-2800 BCE copper item that left significant traces of matter with the observed C-14 dating.<ref name=\"Bryant2003p164\"/>\n\n== Vashishtha Temples==\n[[Image:Vashisht temple.jpg|thumb|250px|Vashishtha Temple, in [[Vashisht (Village)|Vashisht]] village, [[Himachal Pradesh]]]]\n\nThere is an Ashram dedicated to Vashishtha in [[Guwahati]], [[India]]. This Ashram is situated close to [[Assam]]-[[Meghalaya]] border to the south of [[Guwahati]] city and is a major tourist attraction of Guwahati. Vashishtha's Temple is situated in [[Vashisht (Village)|Vashisht]] village, Himachal Pradesh. Vashishtha Cave, a cave on the banks of [[Ganges]] at Shivpuri, 18&nbsp;km from [[Rishikesh]] is also locally believed to be his winter abode and houses a Shiva temple, also nearby is Arundhati Cave.\n\nGuru Vashishtha is also the primary deity at [[Arattupuzha Temple]] known as Arattupuzha Sree Dharmasastha in [[Arattupuzha]] village in [[Thrissur]] district of [[Kerala]]. The famous [[Arattupuzha Pooram]] is a yearly celebration where Sri Rama comes from the [[Thriprayar Temple]] to pay obeisance to his Guru at Arattupuzha temple.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Agastya]]\n* [[Aruni]]\n* [[Atri]]\n* [[Kashyapa]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book |last=Chapple |first=Christopher |authorlink=Christopher Chapple |title=The Concise Yoga V\u0101si\u1e63\u1e6dha |translator=[[Swami Venkatesananda|Venkatesananda, Swami]] |contribution=Introduction |publisher=State University of New York Press |location=Albany |year=1984 |isbn=0-87395-955-8 |oclc=11044869 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1FFdOj2dv8cC |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=Robert Lingat |title=The Classical Law of India |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Sauo8iSIj7YC |year=1973 |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=978-0-520-01898-3 }}\n* {{citation |first=Patrick|last= Olivelle|title=Dharmasutras: The Law Codes of Ancient India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gnVxqvPg9a0C|year=1999|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-283882-7 }}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=Patrick Olivelle |title=Between the Empires: Society in India 300 BCE to 400 CE |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=efaOR_-YsIcC |year=2006|publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-977507-1 }}\n*{{cite book |title=The Philosophy of the Yoga Vashista. A Comparative Critical and Synthetic Survey of the Philosophical Ideas of Vashista as presented in the Yoga-Vashista Maha-Ramayan. Based on a thesis approved for the degree of Doctor of Letters in the Banaras Hindu University |publisher=Darshana Printers |location=Moradabad |first=B L |last=Atreya |date=1981|origyear= 1935) |page=467}}\n* {{Cite book |last = Leslie |first = Julia |year = 2003 |title = Authority and meaning in Indian religions: Hinduism and the case of V\u0101lm\u012bki |publisher = Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.  |isbn = 0-7546-3431-0 |url = https://archive.org/details/authoritymeaning00lesl  |url-access = registration |ref = harv }}\n*{{cite book |title=The Vision and the Way of Vashista |publisher=Indian Heritage Trust |location=Madras |first=B L |last=Atreya |date=1993 |oclc=30508760 |page=583}} Selected verses, sorted by subject, in both Sanskrit and English text.\n*{{cite book |title=The Essence of Yogavaasishtha |publisher=Samata Books |location=Chennai |author=V\u0101lm\u012bki |others=Compiled by Sri Jnanananda Bharati, transl. by Samvid |origyear=1982|date=2002 |pages=344}} Sanskrit and English text.\n*{{cite book |title=Yoga Vashista Sara: The Essence of Yoga Vashista |publisher=Sri Ramanasramam |location=Tiruvannamalai |author=V\u0101lm\u012bki |others=trans. Swami Sur\u0113\u015b\u0101nanda |date=1976 |oclc=10560384 |pages=29}} Very short condensation.\n\n{{Rishis of Hindu mythology}}\n{{HinduMythology}}\n{{Rigveda}}\n{{Ramayana}}\n\n[[Category:Hindu sages]]\n[[Category:Indian astrologers]]\n[[Category:Ancient Indian astronomers]]\n[[Category:Ancient astrologers]]\n[[Category:Prajapatis]]\n[[Category:Brahmin gotras]]\n", "name_user": "157.46.58.139", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eMythology)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vasishtha"}
{"title_page": "Lund Cathedral", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox church\n| name                   = Lund Cathedral\n| fullname               = \n| image                  = Lund Cathedral 2017-08-17.jpg\n| imagesize              = \n| imagelink              = \n| imagealt               = \n| caption                = View of Lund Cathedral from the south east\n| coordinates            = {{coord|55|42|15|N|13|11|36|E|region:SE_type:landmark|display=inline}}\n| osgraw                 = \n| osgridref              = \n| location               = [[Lund]]\n| country                = [[Sweden]]\n\n| denomination           = [[Church of Sweden]]\n| previous denomination  = [[Church of Denmark]] (until 1658)<br>[[Catholic Church]] (until the [[Reformation in Denmark\u2013Norway and Holstein|Reformation]]\n| churchmanship          = \n| membership             = \n| attendance             = \n| website                = [http://www.lundsdomkyrka.se/ Website of the Cathedral]\n\n| former name            = \n| bull date              = \n| founded date           = late 11th century\n| founder                = \n| dedication             = \n| dedicated date         = \n| consecrated date       = 1123 (crypt)<br>1145 (main altar)\n| cult                   = \n| relics                 = \n| events                 = \n| past bishop            = \n| people                 = \n\n| status                 = Active\n| functional status      = Cathedral\n| heritage designation   = [[Listed buildings in Sweden|Ecclesiastical monument]] in the buildings database of the [[Swedish National Heritage Board]].<ref name=raa>{{cite web |url= http://www.bebyggelseregistret.raa.se/bbr2/anlaggning/visaHistorik.raa?anlaggningId=21300000022524&page=historik&visaHistorik=true|title= Lund kn, DOMKYRKAN 1 LUNDS DOMKYRKA|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Bebyggelseregistret|publisher= [[Swedish National Heritage Board]]|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n| designated date        = \n| architect              = Donatus<br>[[Adam van D\u00fcren]]<br>[[Carl Georg Brunius]]<br>[[Helgo Zettervall]]\n| architectural type     = \n| style                  = \n| groundbreaking         = \n| completed date         = \n| construction cost      = \n| closed date            = \n| demolished date        = \n\n| capacity               = \n| length                 = {{convert|85|m|ft}}{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=11}}\n| width                  = {{convert|30|m|ft}}{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=11}}\n| width nave             = \n| height                 = {{convert|55|m|ft}} (to the top of the towers){{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=48}}\n| diameter               = \n| other dimensions       = \n| floor area             = \n| dome quantity          = \n| dome height outer      = \n| dome height inner      = \n| dome dia outer         = \n| dome dia inner         = \n| spire quantity         = \n| spire height           = \n| materials              = \n\n| diocese                = [[Diocese of Lund]]\n| bishop                 = [[Johan Tyrberg]]\n| logo                   = \n| logosize               = \n| logolink               = \n| logoalt                = \n}}\n'''Lund Cathedral''' ({{lang-sv|Lunds domkyrka}}) is a [[cathedral]] of the [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] [[Church of Sweden]] in [[Lund]], [[Scania]], Sweden. It is the seat of the [[List of bishops of Lund|Bishop of Lund]] and the main church of the [[Diocese of Lund]]. It was built as the [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] cathedral of the archiepiscopal see of all the Nordic countries, dedicated to [[Lawrence of Rome|Saint Lawrence]]. It is one of the oldest stone buildings still in use in Sweden.\n\nLund Cathedral has been called \"the most powerful representative of [[Romanesque architecture]] in the [[Nordic countries]]\". Its main altar was consecrated in 1145 and the cathedral was by that time largely finished; the western towers were built somewhat later. Its architecture show clear influences from contemporary north Italian architecture, conveyed via the [[Rhine Valley]]. The earliest architect was named Donatus, though his precise role in the construction of the cathedral is difficult to determine. The new cathedral was richly decorated with stone sculpture, including two unusual statues in the crypt traditionally called \"The giant Finn and his wife\" about which a local legend has developed. The cathedral was severely damaged in a fire in 1234, and major restoration works were carried out in the early 16th century under the leadership of [[Adam van D\u00fcren]]. Following the [[Reformation in Denmark\u2013Norway and Holstein|Reformation]], the cathedral suffered from lost income and dilapidation. In 1658 the city of Lund and the cathedral became a part of Sweden following the [[Treaty of Roskilde]]. Lund Cathedral was the site of the ceremony founding [[Lund University]] in 1688. Repairs were made during the 18th century but in 1832 a complete restoration of the cathedral was recommended. Subsequently much of the cathedral was restored and rebuilt during most of the 19th century. The work was first led by [[Carl Georg Brunius]] and later by architect [[Helgo Zettervall]] and not entirely finished until 1893. The changes done during the 19th century went very far; among other things, Zettervall had the entire western part, including the towers, demolished and rebuilt to his own designs.\n\nThe medieval cathedral contains several historic furnishings and pieces of art. Its main altarpiece was donated to the cathedral in 1398, and it also contains [[Gothic art|Gothic]] choir stalls, bronzes and an [[astronomical clock]] from the 15th century (although heavily restored in 1923). When it was built, Lund Cathedral was lavishly decorated with Romanesque stone sculptures. It also contains late medieval stone sculptures from the time of Adam van D\u00fcren's renovation. After the Reformation the cathedral was also equipped with a decorated [[pulpit]]. Of more recent date is the large [[mosaic]] in the [[apse]], by [[Joakim Skovgaard]], installed in 1927. Lund Cathedral has six [[church organ]]s, one of which is the largest in Sweden, and is also used as a concert venue.\n\n==Historical background==\nChristian missionaries from present-day Germany and England were active in the [[Christianization of Scandinavia|Christianisation of Denmark]], and Denmark eventually became part of the [[Prince-Archbishopric of Bremen|Archdiocese of Hamburg-Bremen]]. With the consolidation of Danish monarchy during the second half of the 11th century, and with a political crisis in continental Europe, there arose an opportunity for the Danish monarchs to bypass the German influence over church policy in Denmark.{{sfn|Ryd\u00e9n|1999|p=99\u2013100}} An [[episcopal see]] was created in Lund in 1060.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=25}} At the same time, another see was created in [[Dalby, Lund Municipality|Dalby]], very close to Lund. However, when the first bishop of Lund ([[Henry of Lund]]) died, the erstwhile bishop of Dalby, [[Egino (Bishop of Dalby)|Egino]], was installed in Lund and Dalby abandoned as the seat of a bishop. At the same time, in 1103, Lund was proclaimed an archiepiscopal see covering all Nordic countries.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=25\u201329}}{{sfn|Wrangel|1923|p=4\u20135}}\n\nSome kind of rudimentary settlement probably existed at the site of Lund Cathedral at the end of the 10th and early 11th centuries, but no remains of buildings have been found there.{{sfn|Cinthio|1990|p=1}} Lund Cathedral is one of the oldest stone buildings still in use in Sweden.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=7}} During the [[Middle Ages]], the cathedral was surrounded by several buildings serving the diocese, of which only [[Liberiet]], which at one point served as a library, survives.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=69\u201371}}\n\n==History==\n===Foundation and construction===\n[[File:Lund domkyrka - crypt (by Pudelek).JPG|thumb|right|The crypt, the oldest part of Lund Cathedral]]\n[[File:Lund Dom Chor.JPG|thumb|right|The [[apse]] is the most well-preserved part of the original exterior]]\nThe earliest written mention of a church in Lund dedicated to [[Saint Lawrence]] \u2014 the patron saint of Lund Cathedral during the Middle Ages \u2014 dates from 1085.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=37}} Slightly later sources mention both a new and an old church dedicated to Saint Lawrence.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=38}} During the 1940s, archaeological excavations in the cathedral uncovered the foundations of another church inside the present building. The exact age, shape and function of this predecessor to the cathedral has been a matter of some debate.{{sfn|Cinthio|1957|p=1\u201342}}{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=62\u201364}} Most scholars believe that construction of a church on the site of Lund Cathedral was begun sometime during the second half of the 11th century.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=11}} Some time thereafter a new church was begun in almost the same place, but to a larger design in the form of the present cathedral. Parts of the earlier church may have been incorporated in the walls of the cathedral.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=11}} The decision to abandon Dalby as a bishopric and make Lund the sole archbishopric in Scandinavia may have promted the change of plans.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=40}}\n\nApart from the obscurity which thus surrounds the very beginning of the history of the cathedral, the construction of Lund Cathedral is probably among the most well documented among any [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque churches]].{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=28}} Two contemporary accounts of the building of the cathedral, in the form of the [[illuminated manuscripts]] ''{{ill|Necrologium Lundense|sv}}'' and ''{{ill|Liber daticus vetustior|sv}}'', are still preserved in the library of [[Lund University]]. Both books contain notes, written in [[Latin language|Latin]], with dates on the progression of the construction. The oldest part of the cathedral is the large [[crypt]]. Its main [[altar]] was inaugurated on 30 June 1123, followed by the north (1126) and south (1131) side altars in the crypt. Only then did the cathedral begin the be used.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=28}} The main altar of the cathedral was dedicated to [[Mary, mother of Jesus|Saint Mary]] and Saint Lawrence in 1145, by the second archbishop of Lund, [[Eskil of Lund|Eskil]], in a ceremony attended by bishops from present-day Germany, Denmark and Sweden.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=29\u201330}} By then, the construction of the cathedral to more or less its present dimensions was complete.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=30}}{{sfn|Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|2004|p=186\u2013187}}\n\nUnusually for that time, the architect of the cathedral is known by his name, Donatus.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=11}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=30}}{{sfn|Wrangel|1923|p=164}} The name appears in both the ''Necrologium Lundense'' (as \"Donatus architectus\") and the ''Liber daticus vetustior''. Donatus may have been responsible for the layout of the crypt and the cathedral above ground as far west as the current north and south portals of the cathedral, although it is difficult to draw any definitive conclusions about his precise role.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=30}}{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=64}} The same is true for his successor, possibly a builder named Ragnar.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=32}} The building erected during the time of Donatus and his successor show clear influences from Romanesque architecture in [[Lombardy]], conveyed via the [[Rhine Valley]].{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=66}} Donatus himself appears to have been from, or at least educated in, Lombardy.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=58}} [[Speyer Cathedral]] in western Germany is stylistically closely related to Lund Cathedral (especially the crypt), and it has been proposed that Donatus came to Lund from Speyer, where construction more or less ceased in 1106 following the death of [[Henry IV, Holy Roman Emperor|Emperor Henry IV]].{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=59}}{{sfn|Wrangel|1923|p=148}} Similarities have also frequently been pointed out between Lund Cathedral and [[Mainz Cathedral]], and the design of the apse is similar to that of the [[Basilica of Saint Servatius]] in [[Maastricht]].{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=68}} On a more general level, the origins of the style of Lund Cathedral can be found in [[Basilica of Sant'Ambrogio]] ([[Milan]]), [[Modena Cathedral]] and several churches in [[Pavia]], all in northern Italy.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=62}} Similar stylistic influences can be seen in other cathedrals in Denmark from the same time, e.g. in [[Ribe Cathedral]].{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=64}}\n\nThe building of Lund Cathedral must have involved a large number of people and was a collective undertaking.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=68}} Comparable but somewhat later workshops at [[Cologne Cathedral]] and [[Uppsala Cathedral]] employed a workforce of about 100 and 60 people, respectively.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=68}} The project was instrumental in establishing a workshop where local craftsmen could be educated, and thus disseminating artistic influences from continental Europe in Scandinavia. The stone sculptors {{ill|Carl stenm\u00e4stare|sv}}, {{ill|M\u00e5rten stenm\u00e4stare|sv}} and [[Majestatis]] were probably all Scandinavians who were educated at the construction site.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=62}} Many early Romanesque stone churches in the countryside, particularly in Scania but also in the rest of Sweden, show direct influences from Lund Cathedral, notably {{ill|V\u00e4 Church|sv|V\u00e4 kyrka}} (Scania).{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=79\u201381}}{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=265\u2013281}} Other examples are e.g. {{ill|Lannaskede Old Church|sv|Lannaskede gamla kyrka}} ([[Sm\u00e5land]]), {{ill|Hogstad Church|sv|Hogstads kyrka}} ([[\u00d6sterg\u00f6tland]]) and [[Havdhem Church]] ([[Gotland]]).{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=90\u201392}}\n\n===Fire and repairs===\nThe plan and layout of the building consecrated in 1145 was by and large similar to the one see today. A noticeable difference was that the entire choir was separated from the nave by a wall and reserved for the clergy. The towers were also not built until a few decades later.{{sfn|Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|2014|p=187}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=52}} The intention was probably to provide the cathedral with [[vault (architecture)|vaults]], but instead a flat wooden ceiling was installed.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=68\u201369}} The cathedral was adorned with [[Church murals in Sweden|wall paintings]] and almost certainly by [[Medieval stained glass in Sweden|stained glass windows]], but none of these remain.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=66}} In 1234, the cathedral was heavily damaged by a large fire.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=78}} Large donations were to the church in the following years, to allow for repairs.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=74}} Even so, repairs were continuously made during the entire 13th century.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=80}} Following the fire, the burnt-out ceiling was replaced by [[brick]] vaults.{{sfn|Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|2014|p=187}} Changes were also made to the layout of the westernmost part of the building.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=76}} A conflict erupted between King [[Christopher I of Denmark]] and Archbishop [[Jakob Erlandsen]] in 1257 partially because the choir had been enlarged and the seats of the royal family moved, itself a testimony of the growing power of the Church.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=76\u201378}} Two [[chapel]]s were added to the cathedral during the 14th and 15th centuries; one located adjacent to the two westernmost [[Bay (architecture)|bays]] of the south aisle of the nave, and the other as a southern extension of the east transept.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=80\u201381}} [[Buttress]]es were also added piecemeal to the building during the 13th and 14th centuries, to stabilise the building which was under strain from the new, heavier vaults, the added chapels and the constant ringing of the 8.5 [[tonne]] [[church bell]].{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=86\u201387}}\n\n===Changes by Adam van D\u00fcren and later===\n[[File:Lunds domkyrka - KMB - 16001000533737.jpg|thumb|right|A drawing of the cathedral as it appeared in 1750]]\nThe German sculptor and builder [[Adam van D\u00fcren]] apparently worked intermittently at restoring and altering the cathedral between {{circa}} 1506 or 1507 and 1524.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=90\u201391}} Despite, and to some extent because of, the work that had been done during the preceding centuries since the great fire of 1234, the cathedral was in need of a thorough restoration.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=87}} Adam van D\u00fcren and his workshop made several changes and contributions. A new drainage system was installed in the crypt, and as part of that work a [[well]], which probably replaced an earlier well in the same location, was decorated with [[satire|satirical]] [[allegory|allegories]].{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=12}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=88\u201395}} The workshop of van D\u00fcren also created two new windows in the choir, built a large buttress to support the southern transept (before 1513), and rebuilt the [[gable]] of the northern transept (1524) as well as its vaults. New and considerably larger windows with [[Pointed arch (architecture)|pointed arches]] were installed in both the northern wall of the north transept and in the southern wall of the south transept.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=12}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=100}} The towers and western facade were also repaired in 1512\u201318 and again in 1527.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=91}} It has been argued that the cathedral may have collapsed, were it not for the work done by van D\u00fcren.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=104}}\n\nFollowing the Reformation in the 16th century, the diocese lost much of its revenues.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=126}} The building was still subjected to much stress, not least by the use of the large church bell, and suffered during the recurrent [[List of wars involving Denmark|wars between Denmark and Sweden]]; in 1658 Lund permanently became part of Sweden. Despite van D\u00fcren's repairs, the church was described as being \"very dilapidated\" in 1682.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=128}} During the 18th century, the chapels of the church were used for funerals, but also as an improvised [[morgue]] where corpses were occasionally left for several years.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=130}} Attempts at repairs were made; among them the entire apse was dismantled and then re-erected.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=12}} Many of the repairs were however either temporary or outright detrimental to condition of the building. King [[Gustav III of Sweden]] visited the cathedral crypt in 1785 and expressed his displeasure at its state.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=13}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=132}} In 1812, the aforementioned chapels from the 14th and 15th centuries were demolished.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=134}}\n\n===Changes by Carl Georg Brunius and Helgo Zettervall===\n[[File:Demolition of the tower of Lund Cathedral.jpg|thumb|right|Demolition of the south tower of the cathedral during the time of Zettervall]]\nWhen the congregation wanted to build a new [[church organ]] in the early 19th century, architect {{ill|Axel Nystr\u00f6m|sv|Axel Nystr\u00f6m (1793\u20131868)}} was invited to examine the situation in 1832. Nystr\u00f6m recommended a complete renovation of the cathedral.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=134}} The chairman of the council in charge of administering the cathedral buildings, [[Carl Georg Brunius]], was called to execute the plans of Nystr\u00f6m, and he did so while also making changes according to his own convictions. He also wrote the first systematic art history of the cathedral.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=135}} Brunius had the organ moved, the crypt repaired, installed a set of steps connecting the choir with the nave and improved the drainage system.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=135}} He also removed modern furnishings, re-built some of the buttresses and changed the stone of a large part of the facade.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=121}} Brunius retired due to old age in 1859, but as there was still a substantial need for repairs, the young architect [[Helgo Zettervall]] appointed to carry out the rest of the work in 1860.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=121\u2013122}} A conflict between Brunius and Zettervall developed almost immediately, but Zettervall would keep working on restoring the cathedral until 1893 and ultimately got his will through, for the most part.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=135}}{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=121\u2013181}} A compromise in 1862 proposed that the Danish architect [[Ferdinand Meldahl]] would assume the main responsibility, and Zettervall would merely assist Meldahl. However, it soon became apparent that Zettervall would not accept a subordinate role and Meldahl himself showed little interest in the project.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=141}} In 1862 Zettervall traveled extensively through Germany and Italy to study stylistically related architecture, and also to visit the latest examples of building restoration so that he could draw upon that experience in his work at Lund.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=134\u2013141}} In 1863, he presented a first proposal for a complete restoration of the cathedral. Zettervall himself considered it a \"reasonable middle ground between reparation and reconstruction\".{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=142}} The proposal would mean the removal of all buttresses, a new roof, completely rebuilt towers, and the removal of the large Gothic windows in the transepts. Zettervall also proposed to add an octagonal dome over the [[Crossing (architecture)|crossing]]. Far-reaching changes would also affect the interior. In the proposal Zettervall strove to reduce and refine the building volumes of the cathedral and create a unified composition of block-like elements.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=142\u2212152}}\n\nThe proposal by Zettervall was criticised, not least by Meldahl. Zettervall re-worked the proposal and put forward a revised, less far-reaching proposal in 1864, notably without the central dome.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=152}} This proposal was also rejected and the plan for a complete overhaul abandoned; however it was at the same time decided that Zettervall would continue working on repairing the cathedral and every year make what changes that were deemed necessary. In this way, Zettervall could piecemeal over the next decades in effect rebuild the cathedral largely in line with the proposal from 1864.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=135}}{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=158\u2013159}}\n\nThe cathedral was radically transformed by the work of Brunius and Zettervall. All windows were replaced, several vaults and pillars were repaired or rebuilt, and both architects effected extensive changes to the transept. Just as he had suggested, Zettervall had all the buttresses removed and demolished the entire western part of the church, including the towers, and rebuilt them according to his own [[Romanesque Revival architecture|Neo-Romanesque]] designs.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=13\u201314}}<ref name=byggnaden>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/rundtur/byggnaden/|title= En kyrka i st\u00e4ndig f\u00f6r\u00e4ndring|trans-title= A constantly changing church|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\nIn the 20th century, archaeological excavations were carried out in and around the cathedral. The building also underwent a major restoration in 1954\u20131963, led by architect {{ill|Eiler Gr\u00e6be|sv}}. During this time the decorative painting from the 19th century was removed.<ref name=byggnaden/> The large [[mosaic]] decorating the apse was installed in 1927, to designs by [[Joakim Skovgaard]].{{sfn|Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|2014|p=187}}{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=14}} In 1990 the layout of the choir was changed and the altar placed in the crossing.<ref name=byggnaden/> [[Pope Francis]] visited the cathedral on 31 October 2016 to observe the 499th anniversary of the [[Protestant Reformation|Reformation]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Anderson|first1=Christina|title=Pope Francis, in Sweden, Urges Catholic-Lutheran Reconciliation|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/01/world/europe/pope-francis-in-sweden-urges-catholic-lutheran-reconciliation.html|accessdate=1 November 2016|work=The New York Times|date=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Architecture and decoration==\nLund Cathedral has been called \"the most powerful representative of Romanesque architecture in the Nordic countries\".{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=11}} It lies at some distance from any other buildings and dominates its surroundings.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=181}} It consists of the two towers built by Zettervall, which flank the main entrance to the west. Behind them a [[nave]] with two [[aisle]] opens up to a [[transept]] that is somewhat higher than the nave. A short flight of stairs thus connect the nave with the [[choir (architecture)|choir]] as well as with the crypt under the choir. The choir ends in an apse. Inside, the bays of the cathedral are supported by [[groin vault]]s. The number of bays in the aisles are the double of that in the nave. The arches that separate the nave from the aisles are supported by piers and pillars of alternating width. The crypt has over forty shallow [[groin vault]]s supported by pillars with cushion-cap capitals. It is sparsely lit by low small windows.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=68}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=45}}\n\nSeen from outside, the different elements of the building are clearly discernible as independent volumes, \"as if they could be taken apart and put together again\".{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=181}} The apse of the cathedral is a \"forcefully articulated\" semi-circle in three storeys.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=68}} The apse is the most well-preserved part of the Romanesque building and has been described as \"the artistic high point of the exterior\".{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=124}} The southern portal of the nave is perhaps the oldest of the cathedral. Five decorated [[archivolt]]s supported by small columns with variously decorated [[capital (architecture)|capitals]], frame a [[tympanon]] depicting the [[Lamb of God]].{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=70\u201371}} The northern portal is slightly later and more richly decorated. It's tympanon depicts Samson wrestling with the lion.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=72\u201373}} Two bronze doors built by {{ill|Carl Johan Dyfverman|sv|Carl Johan Dyfverman (konstn\u00e4r)}} serve as the main entrance in the centre of the west facade. They have 24 reliefs with subjects from the Bible, particularly the Old Testament. Above the doorway, the tympanon depicts Christ, Canute IV of Denmark and Saint Lawrence.<ref name=byggnaden/> The cathedral has two [[sacristy|sacristies]].{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=48}} The building material of the cathedral is mostly [[sandstone]] quarried in the area around [[H\u00f6\u00f6r]]. The main walls are constructed as shells of sandstone filled with [[fieldstone]] mixed with [[lime mortar]]. The thickness of the walls is around {{convert|2 to 3|m|ft}}.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=126\u2013127}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=48}} \n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" caption=\"Overview of Lund Cathedral\" heights=\"175px\">\nFile:Lunds domkyrka. Plan.png|Plan\nFile:Lunds domkyrka\u2013flygbild 06 september 2014.jpg|Aerial view from the south east\nFile:Lund Cathedral 2017-08-17 4.jpg|View from the entrance towards east\nFile:Lund cathedral interior 2015-03-30-4746.jpg|View from the altar towards west\n</gallery>\n\n===Sculptures===\n[[File:Finn the Giant, Lund Cathedral crypt 2017-08-17 1.jpg|thumb|right|\"The giant Finn\" in the crypt, probably a depiction of the biblical hero Samson]]\nWhen it comes to stone sculpture, Lund Cathedral was the most lavishly decorated Romanesque building to be built in the Nordic countries.{{sfn|Svanberg|1995|p=152}} Perhaps the most well-known and striking of these are the sculptures of two figures traditionally called \"The giant [[Fin (troll)|Finn]] and his wife\" in the crypt.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=75}} According to a local legend, the giant helped build the cathedral, but when he was not payed for his services he tried to destroy it by shaking the pillars, but was petrified.<ref name=finn>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/fordjupning/jatten-finn/|title= J\u00e4tten Finn vakar \u00f6ver kryptan|trans-title= The giant Finn watches over the crypt|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref> The larger of the two figures is embracing a column, while the smaller is attached to another column with a rope. These sculptures have probably been the subject of more attempts at an explanation than any other medieval artworks in Sweden.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=77}} Most scholars today believe thelarger sculpture depicts [[Samson]], but what the smaller figure is supposed to represent is not know. The sculptures date from the construction of the crypt but have been treated poorly, especially during the 18th century, and lost much of their original detailing.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=77}}\n\nThe fluted columns also found in the crypt are similar in style to [[Norman architecture|English Norman architecture]] and may indicate that the very first artistic influences came from the area bordering the [[English Channel]].{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=64\u201365}} Apart from these columns however, the rich stone ornamentation is clearly Lombard in style, i.e. related to north Italian art of the period.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=66}} A [[baldachin]] now immured in the east wall of the north transept may have been part of the original western facade; Its columns have [[Corinthian order|Corinthian capitals]] and support a richly decorated archivolt on which traces of original paint survives. Opposite, in the south wall, is a smaller baldachin where the columns themselves are sculpted angels (one with [[feather tights]]) standing on lions. Similar sculptures exist in e.g. [[Como]] and Modena in northern Italy.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=74\u201375}} In addition, the capitals of the columns in the church are all of high artisanal quality, and can be broadly divided into two groups displaying either [[Classical architecture|Classical]] or [[Byzantine architecture|Byzantine]] influences.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=75}} Apart from its rich Romanesque decoration, Lund Cathedral also contains several late medieval sculptures made by Adam van D\u00fcren, as mentioned above. Several of these are of animals and contain inscriptions in [[Low German]]. A relief in the south transept displaying the [[Woman of the Apocalypse]] flanked by Saint Lawrence and Saint Canute is similar to the portal relief van D\u00fcren made a couple of years earlier at [[Glimmingehus]].{{sfn|Svanberg|1996|p=196\u2013197}}\n\n===Altarpiece===\nThe medieval main [[altarpiece]] was donated to the cathedral in 1398 by [[Ide Pedersdatter Falk]].<ref name=kor>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/rundtur/hogkoret/|title= Gyllene mosaik och korstolar fr\u00e5n 1300-talet|trans-title= Golden mosaics and choir stalls from the 14th century|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref> The altarpiece is stylistically similar to a group of altarpieces from northern Germany. Its central panel depicts the [[Coronation of the Virgin]], surrounded by two rows of 40 saints, 26 of which are original. 12 figures have been taken from other medieval altarpieces, while two of the added figures are from the 17th century. The altarpiece is {{convert|7.6|m|ft}} wide but is missing an original pair of wings.{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=20\u201323}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=112\u2013113}}\n\n===Choir stalls===\n[[File:Lunds Domkyrka korstolar h\u00f6ger om koret.JPG|thumb|right|The right side of the choir, showing parts of the choir stalls (right) and the main altarpiece (left)]]\nThe choir contains two rows of medieval choir stalls containing in total 78 seats. The wooden stalls date from the end of the 14th century, probably commissioned by archbishop Nils J\u00f6nson some time between 1361 and 1379. They were clearly made by several different wood carvers. They are approximately {{convert|3|m|ft}} tall without their gables and decorated with carved details. These are biblical scenes from both the [[Old Testament|Old]] and [[New Testament]], but the stalls also contain [[misericord]]s portraying animals and other small details. Their style is [[Gothic art|High Gothic]] and they are stylistically linked with contemporary art from the Rhine Valley. They are among the largest wooden Gothic sculptures to survive in the Nordic countries, and have been described as being of internationally high quality.{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=24\u201332}} The choir stalls in Lund Cathedral also lent stylistic inspiration to the choir stalls in [[Roskilde Cathedral]] and [[St. Bendt's Church, Ringsted]].{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=24\u201332}}{{sfn|Dun\u00e9r|1984|p=1\u20139}}\n\nSlightly older than the choir stalls is a [[Cathedra|bishop's throne]] which survives in a damaged state and is placed in the south transept. It is somewhat similar in construction to the choir stalls but stylistically different and more closely related to contemporary art from north Germany.{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=32\u201335}}\n\n===Astronomical clock===\n{{Main|Horologium mirabile Lundense}}\n[[File:Lunds astronomiska ur-2.jpg|thumb|right|The astronomical clock]]\nThe [[astronomical clock]] of Lund Cathedral, presently located at the west end of the north aisle, dates from the late Middle Ages and was installed in Lund Cathedral {{circa}} 1425. In 1837 it was dismantled. It was restored at the initiative of architect {{ill|Theodor W\u00e5hlin|sv}} and the Danish clock-maker Julius Bertram Larsen and re-inaugurated in 1923. The upper part, which is original, is the clock, while the lower part, a reconstruction, is a calendar. Twice every day the two knights on the top clash their swords. The clock then plays the tune ''[[In dulci jubilo]]'' and a procession of figures parades across the face of the clock.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=125\u2013126}} Three astronomical clocks of similar design are preserved in Europe. The clock in Lund was repaired 2009\u20132010.{{sfn|Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|2014|p=187}}<ref name=svt>{{cite web |url= https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/skane/lund-uret-i-domkyrkan-slutar-sla|title= Lund \u2013 Uret i domkyrkan slutar sl\u00e5|trans-title= The clock in  the cathedral ceases to strike|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 12 October 2009|website= |publisher= [[Sveriges television]]|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref><ref name=uret>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/rundtur/uret/|title= Det underbara uret i Lund|trans-title= The astonishing clock in Lund|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\n===Bronzes===\nThe cathedral also owns three High Gothic [[bronze]] columns carrying statuettes and a seven-branched candelabrum from the end of the Middle Ages. Two of the bronze columns are crowned by angels, and the third one by a statuette of Saint Lawrence, holding a gridiron, the symbol of his martyrdom. It probably dates from the middle of the 14th century, while the two angel-bearing columns may be somewhat later. Saint Lawrence's column is approximately {{convert|3|m|ft}} tall (and the saint {{convert|70|cm|inch}}), while the columns with angels are slightly smaller.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=114}} The three columns were probably made in [[L\u00fcbeck]] or [[Hamburg]]. Presently located in the south transept is also the {{convert|3.5|m|ft}} tall seven-branched candelabrum or candle holder from the late 15th century, manufactured by Harmen Bonstede in Hamburg.<ref name=stake>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/rundtur/sjuarmade-ljusstakens-kapell/|title= V\u00e5r tids martyrer och den sjuarmade ljusstaken|trans-title= The martyrs of our time and the seven-branched candelabrum|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref> It was supplied to the cathedral in a dismantled state, and traces of its assembly instruction is still discernible on the candelabrum. Similar candelabra were installed in a number of Scandinavian cathedrals at approximately the same time; although the one in Lund is larger than those in the cathedrals of [[Aarhus Cathedral|Aarhus]], Ribe, [[Viborg Cathedral|Viborg]] and [[Storkyrkan|Stockholm]].<ref name=stake/>{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=114\u2013116}}\n\n===Pulpit===\nThe current [[pulpit]] was commissioned at the end of the 16th century and is marked with the date 1592. The artist was [[Johannes Ganssog]] from [[Frankfurt an der Oder]] in present-day Germany. It is technically skillfully attached to one of the pillars of the nave, and it is entered through a stair cut inside the pillar. The building material is sandstone, black [[limestone]] and black and white [[marble]], and it is partially painted and [[gilding|gilded]]. Reliefs of [[alabaster]] on the side show scenes from the New Testament.{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=60\u201364}}{{sfn|Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|2014|p=187}}\n\n==Flora==\n[[File:Flickr - Sigfrid Lundberg - Wall-rue, Asplenium ruta-muraria.jpg|thumb|right|Wall-rue growing on the apse]]\nSeveral surveys and descriptions of the [[flora]] of the cathedral, i.e. the plants that grow on its walls, have been made. The first to describe the flora of the cathedral was [[Daniel Rolander]], one of the [[apostles of Linnaeus]], who made a list of the [[vascular plant]]s, [[moss]]es and [[lichen]] he found growing on the building in 1771.{{sfn|Johansson|1993|p=25}} It was rediscovered in the 20th century and published in 1931. [[Elias Magnus Fries]] also made observations about the flora of the cathedral during the first half of the 19th century. More systematic surveys of the flora of the building have been published in 1922 and in 1993 (the latter only encompassing lichen).{{sfn|Johansson|1993|p=25}} Of the species observed growing on the cathedral, the minute [[fern]] [[Asplenium ruta-muraria|wall-rue]] was mentioned as early as 1756 by {{ill|Anders Tidstr\u00f6m|sv}} and is perhaps the most conspicuous member of the cathedral flora.{{sfn|Gertz|1923|p=458}} When the lichen flora was surveyed in 1993, 15 species were discovered. One of these, [[Lecanora perpruinosa]], had not been observed in the province of Scania before.{{sfn|Johansson|1993|p=26}}\n\n==Relationship with Lund University==\n[[Lund University]] was founded in a ceremony in the cathedral in 1688.<ref name=nyckeltal>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/fordjupning/nyckelartal/|title= Ett p\u00e4rlband av h\u00e4ndelser|trans-title= A string of events|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 20 April 2020|quote=}}</ref> Following the Reformation, the choir of the cathedral was for a long time used as a classroom, first by [[Lund Cathedral School]] and later by the university. The university also used the choir to store its [[library]] for some time.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=128\u2013129}} The cathedral is still the place for the ceremony of the conferment of new doctor's degrees at the university.<ref name=universitet>{{cite web |url= https://www.lu.se/om-universitetet/akademiska-hogtider/doktorspromotionen/promotionsdagen|title= Promotionsdagen|trans-title= The day of conferment of the doctor's degree|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= |publisher= [[Lund University]]|access-date= 20 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\nThe cathedral has five [[choir (music)|choirs]] for adults and two choirs for children.<ref name=korer>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/musik-kultur/korer-2/|title= K\u00f6rer|trans-title= Choirs|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 20 April 2020|quote=}}</ref> The cathedral is also frequently used for concerts.\n\nThere are currently six church organs in Lund Cathedral, including the largest church organ in Sweden. The gallery organ was built between 1932 and 1934 by the Danish company [[Marcussen & S\u00f8n]] and renovated by the same company in 1992. It has 102 stops distributed between four manuals and a pedalboard. There are 7,074 pipes in total. The smallest organ is inside the astronomical clock, where it plays ''In dulci jubilo''.<ref name=orglar>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/fordjupning/orglar/|title= Sex orglar i Domkyrkan|trans-title= Six organs in the cathedral|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Works cited==\n*{{cite book |last= Bodin|first= Anders|date= 2017|title= Helgo Zettervalls arkitektur: kyrkor|volume=II|trans-title= The architecture of Helgo Zettervall: churches|url= http://kth.diva-portal.org/smash/get/diva2:1094819/FULLTEXT01.pdf|language= Swedish|location= Stockholm|publisher= Carlssons bokf\u00f6rlag|isbn=9789173317856}}\n*{{cite book |last= Cinthio|first= Erik|date= 1957|title= Lunds domkyrka under romansk tid|trans-title= Lund Cathedral during the Romanesque era|url= https://portal.research.lu.se/portal/files/21557081/Diss_Erik_Cinthio.pdf|language= Swedish|location= Lund|publisher= C. W. K. Gleerup|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last= Cinthio|first= Erik|date= 1990|title= Lunds domkyrkas f\u00f6rhistoria. S:t Laurentiuspatrociniet och Knut den Heliges kyrka \u00e4n en g\u00e5ng|trans-title= The pre-history of Lund Cathedral. The patronage of St. Lawrence and the church of Canute the Holy once more|url= https://www.tidskriftenale.nu/pdfale/ALE-1990-2_v02.pdf|language= Swedish|journal= Ale. Historisk tidskrift f\u00f6r Sk\u00e5ne, Halland och Blekinge|volume= 2|issue= |pages= 1\u201313|doi= |access-date=|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last= Dun\u00e9r|first= Uno|date= 1984|title= Gideon och ullen|trans-title= Gideon and the wool|url= ht